<seg id="1"> Let's again direct our attention to the Iran nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The International Atomic Energy Agency confirmed on the 6th that the Iranian government has written a letter to the IAEA requesting for the removal of all the equipment monitoring Iran's nuclear facilities by the middle of this month. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Due to the IAEA decision to report the Iran nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, Iran has announced the termination of all its support and cooperation measures on the nuclear issue and will no longer allow the IAEA to conduct snap inspection of its nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="4"> In response to the current tensions concerning the Iran nuclear issue, Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov said in Athens, Greece, that the cooperation between Russia and Iran still exists. </seg>
<seg id="5"> This will become the motivation for the resolution to the Iran nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="6"> A Russian Foreign Ministry spokesperson said that day that Russia's proposal to Iran for establishing a joint uranium enrichment enterprise in Russia still stands. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The two sides may conduct negotiations on this issue next week. </seg>
<seg id="8"> On the same day, Lugar, chairman of the US Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said at the UN headquarters in New York that the US does not endorse Israeli attacks on Iran's nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Some recent news report said that Israeli defense experts said that the Israeli Air Force may deal serious blows to Iran's nuclear facilities if necessary. </seg>
<seg id="10"> According to Xinhua News Agency, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Kislyak said on the 7th that Russia is willing to cooperate with Iran on the nuclear issue so as to help Iran obtain the legal right to develop nuclear energy for peaceful purposes. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Kislyak said that Russia's proposal for a joint uranium enrichment enterprise with Iran is still valid now. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Russia hopes to have negotiations with Iran on this issue in the near future. </seg>
<seg id="13"> At the end of December last year, Russia submitted a proposal to Iran regarding the establishment of a joint uranium enrichment enterprise by the two countries in Russia. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Both the EU and the US indicated that they can accept this plan for a compromise. </seg>
<seg id="15"> However, Iran hopes that Russia can continue to revise the original plan. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Kong Quan said on the 7th that though the IAEA reported the Iran nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, it did not hand over the agency's responsibility for handling the Iran nuclear issue to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Therefore, all parties still need to break the deadlock on the Iran nuclear issue within the IAEA framework. </seg>
<seg id="18"> According to the IAEA resolution, IAEA Director General ElBaradei will submit a report on the Iran nuclear issue to the Security Council in March. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The Security Council will make a final decision after evaluating this report. </seg>
<seg id="20"> We think this resolution is asking Iran to fulfill the relevant Security Council resolution and its commitments without submitting or referring the issue to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Recently, China has been seeking a peaceful resolution to the Iran nuclear issue through diplomatic channels. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Kong Quan said that on February 1, Zhang Yan, director-general of Arms Control and Disarmament Department of China's Foreign Ministry, and Larijani, secretary of Iran's Supreme National Security Council and chief nuclear negotiator, held talks on the Iran nuclear issue in Tehran. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The Chinese side hopes that Iran should pay attention to the key issue of the international community and create conditions for peaceful resolution to the Iran nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Solving the Iran nuclear issue within the IAEA framework not only conforms to the interests of the Chinese side but also, as we believe firmly, conforms to the interests of all parties concerned. </seg>
<seg id="25"> For that purpose, we also call upon all relevant parties in the international community again not to abandon diplomatic efforts for this issue. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060208_145800_256_429.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> Hamas, which is currently forming a new Palestinian autonomous government, officially announced that except for the candidate for prime minister, the name list of the new government's cabinet has been basically finalized. </seg>
<seg id="2"> This led outsiders to have a variety of speculations on the candidate for prime minister. </seg>
<seg id="3"> A senior Hamas official disclosed to the Associated Press on the 8th that Hamas is preparing to nominate al-Khudairi, board chairman ((merchant)) of the Islamic University in Gaza, as prime minister of the new autonomous government, but this nomination has not been officially submitted to Abbas. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Backed by Hamas, 50-year-old al-Khudairi participated in the election of the Palestinian Legislative Council as an independent candidate last month. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Al-Khudairi never mentioned violence or anything against Israel in his public speech. </seg>
<seg id="6"> However, he said that Palestine needs internal reforms. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Currently, a senior Hamas delegation is visiting Cairo and discussing with Egypt on the issue of Hamas forming a new Palestinian government. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Khalid Mashal, one of the delegates, told the news media on the 8th that in spite of the pressure that has kept coming from the international community and some Arab countries, the Palestinian government formed by the leadership of Hamas will not recognize Israel. </seg>
<seg id="9"> At the same time, Mashal also warned Abbas in his speech not to willfully change the structure of the Palestinian leadership without prior consultation with Hamas. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Analysts consider this a response to Abbas's plan to appoint Interior Minister Yusuf as deputy commander of the security forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> However, regarding the issue of forming a new Palestinian autonomous government, Mashal refused to confirm the news that Hamas is preparing to nominate al-Khudairi, board chairman ((merchant)) of the Islamic University in Gaza, to serve as prime minister of the government. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Mashal said that the candidate for prime minister has not been finalized. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Prior to Mashal's reiteration of refusing to recognize Israel, Marzouk, another Hamas political leader, said in an interview with Egyptian TV that Hamas will absolutely not recognize the legitimate status of Israel, but the new government will continue to keep contact with Israel in various areas, because recognizing Israel or not is a totally different thing from whether to have contact with it. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Apart from the fresh or old hatred of the three Hamas prime minister candidates against Israel, the issue of the territory has also been a tough question concerning Palestinian-Israeli relations. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Israeli Acting Prime Minister Olmert said in an interview with Israel TV Channel 2 on the 7th that Israel must separate from Palestine by setting permanent borders. </seg>
<seg id="16"> This means that Israel will have to withdraw from part of its territories in the West Bank. </seg>
<seg id="17"> However, Olmert stressed that Israel will continue to control major Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Jordan Valley area and maintain the integrity of Jerusalem. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_NEWS3_CMN_20060216_075800_208_476.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> Hello, everyone, welcome to the China News program. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The Chinese consulate general in Karachi confirmed on the 15th that three Chinese engineers and a Pakistani driver were killed in an attack yesterday in the southwestern Pakistani province of Balochistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Upon learning the news late last night, Chinese State President Hu Jintao showed deep concern for the safety of Chinese engineering and technical personnel in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="4"> He instructed the Foreign Ministry, the Chinese embassy and consulate in Pakistan to require Pakistan to catch the murderers, ensure the safety of Chinese personnel in Pakistan, and properly handle the aftermath arising from the deaths of the victims. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Hu Jintao also extended deep condolences on the death of the Chinese victims and expressed sincere sympathy to the bereaved families. </seg>
<seg id="6"> In accordance with President Hu Jintao's instruction, Foreign Minster Li Zhaoxing made an urgent call to Pakistani Foreign Minister Kasuri before dawn today. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The Chinese embassy and consulate in Pakistan immediately activated the emergency mechanism, and relevant personnel have already rushed to the scene. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Premier Wen Jiabao also made instructions on ensuring the safety of Chinese personnel, handling properly the aftermath, and requesting Pakistan to catch the murderers. </seg>
<seg id="9"> In addition, according to the latest information from the Chinese consulate general in Karachi, the remains of the three Chinese were transported to Karachi early this morning and will be shipped back to China by charter plane in a few days. </seg>
<seg id="10"> After the attack, the Chinese consulate general in Karachi immediately dispatched a three-person task force to the scene and transported the remains of the three Chinese engineers to be placed in a hospital in Karachi. </seg>
<seg id="11"> In the meantime, more than 10 Chinese personnel working in the same place with these people have been called back to Karachi.  At present they are emotionally stabilized. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The attack took place in a town called Hub in southeast Quetta. </seg>
<seg id="13"> On the afternoon of that day, six Chinese engineers who worked in a local cement factory were riding in a car leaving the construction site for their residence when an unidentified criminal on a motorcycle stopped them. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The criminal used a submachine gun to fire a barrage of shots, and three engineers died unfortunately. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Following the attack, a tribal militant organization called "the Balochistan Liberation Army" claimed responsibility for the incident. </seg>
<seg id="16"> The Pakistani Foreign Ministry issued a statement that night strongly condemning the attack and calling it an act of terrorism. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The three Chinese who died in the attack were Long Hongbao, Wei Jianping, and Zhao Bin, technical staff from the Hefei Cement Research and Design Institute in Anhui owned by the China National Building Material Group Corporation. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Qin Gang said today that Chinese government leaders showed deep concern over the incident of the Chinese engineering and technical personnel attacked in Pakistan and required the Pakistani side to ensure the safety of Chinese personnel in Pakistan and to promptly catch the murderers. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Qin Gang said that Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan Zhang Chunxiang has reported the relevant information and made representations to the Pakistani government and military officials. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Pakistan strongly condemned the barbarous and cruel incident and expressed condolences on the death of the Chinese personnel, vowing to catch the murderers and fully cooperate with the Chinese side in dealing with the incident. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The Foreign Ministry is currently coordinating with relevant departments to arrange for the remains of the victims to be shipped back to China as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="22"> A task force dealing with the aftermath formed by the CNBM Hefei Cement Research and Design Institute in Anhui, the institution that sent the victims, left Beijing this morning for Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="23"> Following the incident, China's Ministry of Commerce also formed an emergency task force. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Chen Jian, an assistant to the minister of commerce, said that if safe operation cannot be ensured for the time being, the project of the cement factory will not start. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Only when the safety of working staff is ensured can the construction be continued. </seg>
<seg id="26"> As soon as the ((emergency)) task force was formed, we immediately, er, instructed the frontline personnel to rush to the scene of the incident and make proper investigations of the local situation. </seg>
<seg id="27"> At the same time, we in China verified the identities of the dead within the shortest possible time. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Chen Jian said that the Ministry of Commerce will pay close attention to the settlement of the incident and will actively coordinate with relevant departments to deal with the aftermath. </seg>
<seg id="29"> If safe operation cannot be ensured for the time being, we will ask the Chinese company to stop. </seg>
<seg id="30"> The construction will not be restarted until safe operation is firmly assured. </seg>
<seg id="31"> The project of Attock Line B Cement Factory started in 2004. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The Hefei Cement Research and Design Institute is responsible for providing the complete set of equipment and technical services for the cement factory.  The construction is expected to be completed in the first half of 2006. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_NEWS3_CMN_20060217_075800_447_833.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> The remains of the three Chinese engineers who died in an attack in Pakistan were shipped back to China from Karachi by a Pakistani Air Force charter plane at 7:00 this morning local time. </seg>
<seg id="2"> Let's take a look at a report by our correspondent Tao Ye from Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> On the early morning of the 17th, the remains of the three Chinese engineers, who were killed near Karachi, Pakistan on the 15th, were shipped from the PAF Base Faisal Karachi back to China. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The atmosphere was solemn at the PAF Base Faisal Karachi at dawn. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan Zhang Chunxiang, the interior minister of Sindh Province which has jurisdiction over Karachi, the staff of the Chinese embassy and consulate in Pakistan and the staff of the Chinese company led by Chinese Consul General Sun Chunye bid the final farewell to their murdered compatriots. </seg>
<seg id="6"> All people at the scene led by Ambassador Zhang Chunxiang bowed three times to the three coffins. </seg>
<seg id="7"> After that, soldiers from the Pakistani guard of honor slowly carried the three coffins onto the charter plane provided by the Pakistani side. </seg>
<seg id="8"> They walked together with the Chinese and Pakistani personnel around the plane and finally saw off the murdered Chinese compatriots. </seg>
<seg id="9"> At about 7:20 a.m. the charter plane took off from the airport. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The plane will briefly stop over in the Pakistani capital of Islamabad. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Senior Pakistani government officials will board this charter plane and fly directly from Islamabad to Hefei, China this day. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The plane is expected ((expected)) to arrive in Hefei, China tonight Beijing time. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The charter plane carrying the remains of the victims is expected to arrive in Hefei around 10:00 p.m. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Now, let's connect with correspondent Li Guangyu at Luogang Airport in Hefei. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Hello, Li Guangyu.  Please tell us about how things are going in your place. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Hello, host. </seg>
<seg id="17"> We are not very clear at this point as to the specific time when the plane over there will be landing at the airport here. </seg>
<seg id="18"> What we know now is that their plane from Pakistan will land at Urumqi Airport at 5:30 this afternoon before connecting to a flight from Urumqi to Hefei. </seg>
<seg id="19"> I guess it will arrive around 11:00 or 12:00 tonight. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Regarding what specific ceremony there will be when the remains arrive with them tonight,, and who will show up, er, it is still not very clear at this time. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Well, what we know now is that this afternoon the provincial government and, er, the relevant people from the Cement and Design Institute held some, held a coordination meeting, er, that is, to coordinate some activities tonight. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Er, now the work unit, er, the cement institute here, in the past two days, has formed a bereavement counseling team headed by the chairman of the workers' union.  It has been offering some bereavement counseling at homes of the victims' families here. </seg>
<seg id="23"> As for the specific figure of compensation, we do not have any confirmed and specific answer yet. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Er, we learned that among others there is a four hundred thousand yuan insurance policy for, er, accidental casualties. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Er, the families have not directly contacted the insurance company for compensation.  Rather, their work unit is negotiating with the compensation company, er, the insurance company about the compensation on their behalf. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Er, that's all I have learned now. </seg>
<seg id="27"> OK, thanks, Li Guangyu, for your on-site report. </seg>
<seg id="28"> In addition, at noon today, a total of 11 personnel from the Hefei Cement Research and Design Institute who are in Balochistan, Pakistan, including Yuan Fengyu, Xue Jijun, and Yang Wei who survived the February 15 terrorist attack flew back to Hefei. </seg>
<seg id="29"> When the plane carrying the three survivors and 11 other personnel arrived in Hefei, people waiting at the airport heaved a long sigh of relief. </seg>
<seg id="30"> I feel very happy and relieved to be able to come back safely. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Our country is also (()) paying great attention to this incident. </seg>
<seg id="32"> After the incident occurred, it made proper arrangements for them. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Now they will also be escorted home safely. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Anhui provincial officials, along with officials from the China National Building Material Group Corporation, went to the airport to meet the 11 personnel and expressed consolation to them. </seg>
<seg id="35"> We express our sad condolence on the death of our comrades in this unexpected incident in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="36"> We express our warm welcome to the other eleven comrades who are able to return to the motherland safely today. </seg>
<seg id="37"> According to the briefing of the relevant parties, the compensation for the three victims and bereavement counseling to their families are now being carried out. </seg>
<seg id="38"> Although the remains of the three Chinese engineers who died in the attack have been shipped back to China, the investigation into the attack in Pakistan is still underway. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Just an hour ago, that is, 20:00 Beijing time, Pakistani police held a meeting with the staff of the Chinese embassy and consulate in Pakistan to brief the Chinese side on the investigation progress of this incident. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Let's now connect with our correspondent Tao Ye in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Hello, Tao Ye. </seg>
<seg id="42"> Ah, hello, (()). </seg>
<seg id="43"> Yes. </seg>
<seg id="44"> At the meeting %pw just now, </seg>
<seg id="45"> (()) </seg>
<seg id="46"> at the briefing just now, what information was given with regard to the progress of investigation? </seg>
<seg id="47"> Ah, OK. </seg>
<seg id="48"> Just as you said, an hour ago, the police chief, that person named Jacob, in Balochistan, Pakistan, that is, the place where the incident occurred, came to the Chinese consulate general in %pw Karachi to brief our ambassador in Pakistan and consulate general on the investigation by Pakistani police of the incident during these two days. </seg>
<seg id="49"> In his briefing he summarized the main clues and targets Pakistani police currently have in investigating the murderers. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Er, they believe that this incident should have been committed by outsiders, but there surely was connection with some local residents. </seg>
<seg id="51"> Well, they have now shifted their focus to, er, er, some employees hired by the company the Chinese engineers worked for. </seg>
<seg id="52"> They believe that these people may have provided some clues, provided some information to the murderers, such as when the Chinese engineers were leaving, arriving, and at what places. </seg>
<seg id="53"> In addition, they may have also provided some cover for these murderers. </seg>
<seg id="54"> Well, this is the current focus of police investigation. </seg>
<seg id="55"> According to this police chief, he said that during two days of investigation, they have inquired about more than 50 people. </seg>
<seg id="56"> Right now, the scope of investigation is being narrowed down. </seg>
<seg id="57"> In addition, following the briefing, the police chief and other police officials also went to pay their respects to, er, the three deceased in the mourning hall set up in our consulate general in Karachi. </seg>
<seg id="58"> Er, in addition, well, there is a more interesting thing.  That is, earlier it was persistently said that the Balochistan Liberation Army (()) claimed responsibility for the incident, but this information has so far not been officially confirmed by Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="59"> Er, when asked about this by our reporter, the police chief replied by saying that this terrorist organization is actually a very loosely structured organization and does not have a full entity. </seg>
<seg id="60"> Well, er, many people claim they are members of this organization. </seg>
<seg id="61"> Well, so, as far as the Pakistani side is concerned, they, er, still focus their investigation on many specific individuals. </seg>
<seg id="62"> They don't take this organization as a really crucial factor. </seg>
<seg id="63"> OK. </seg>
<seg id="64"> OK, Tao Ye. </seg>
<seg id="65"> (()) </seg>
<seg id="66"> Eh, we will continue to watch for relevant investigation developments. </seg>
<seg id="67"> Thanks, Tao Ye, for your on-site report. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="NTDTV_NTDNEWS12_CMN_20060208_115801_352_611.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> Danish Prime Minister Rasmussen held a press conference at the Prime Minister's Residence on Tuesday. </seg>
<seg id="2"> He said that the current development of the incident concerning the cartoons of Muhammad, founder of Islam, is being taken advantage of by extremists. </seg>
<seg id="3"> He ((stated)) that Denmark respects all religious beliefs and calls for the same right of everyone.  Er, he also called on Muslims to remain restrained and not to appeal to violence. </seg>
<seg id="4"> At 4:30 p.m. on the 7th, Prime Minister Rasmussen and the foreign minister held a press conference at Denmark's Prime Minister's Residence. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Rasmussen said. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The violent incidents occurring at the embassies of several European countries are no longer something between Muslim countries and Denmark. </seg>
<seg id="7"> It is very important for the Danish government and Danish people to get the broad support of the international community to resolve this tough issue. </seg>
<seg id="8"> We are allied with France. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Some organizations of other European countries and the United States in Muslim countries are cooperating closely. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Just a few minutes ago, US President Bush made a phone call here. </seg>
<seg id="11"> In the phone call, he expressed support for Denmark, standing by Denmark. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Rasmussen said, we also think that we should resolve this issue through dialogue and tolerance, not through violence. </seg>
<seg id="13"> We stress freedom and democracy, and respect the precious value of religious belief. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Today I appeal to people in all Muslim countries to work together to suppress violence and prevent it from spreading. </seg>
<seg id="15"> We need to resolve the issue through dialogue, not through violence. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Today we are facing growing international developments of the incident. </seg>
<seg id="17"> We saw the Danish national flag burnt and the embassy damaged. </seg>
<seg id="18"> We saw Danish people being considered intolerant people and the enemy of Islam. </seg>
<seg id="19"> This is wrong. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Extremists and radicals are taking advantage of the incident of cultural conflict to escalate the situation. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Rasmussen stressed, we, Denmark and Danish people, are not the enemy of Islam and other religions. </seg>
<seg id="22"> For generations, Danish people have been pursuing human rights, democracy, and freedom beyond politics. </seg>
<seg id="23"> We will continue to strive for that. </seg>
<seg id="24"> This is part of Denmark's history and also a fundamental part of Danish society. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Denmark is one of the most tolerant and open countries in the world. </seg>
<seg id="26"> We respect all religious beliefs. </seg>
<seg id="27"> We stop violence. </seg>
<seg id="28"> We believe everyone has equal rights. </seg>
<seg id="29"> NTD correspondents Li Luo and Dan Ni reporting from Copenhagen, Denmark. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Angry with the publication of the cartoons of Muhammad, Iranian extremists attacked the Danish embassy in Tehran again on Tuesday, throwing gas bombs. </seg>
<seg id="31"> In the meantime, a state-owned Iranian newspaper, in retaliation, held a contest on cartoons about the Nazi Holocaust. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The United States denounced the move as taking the opportunity to reinforce Iranian President Ahmadinejad's persistent outrageous anti-Israeli practices. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Some twenty to thirty protesters climbed over the wall and entered the Danish embassy compound in Iran. </seg>
<seg id="34"> In addition, more than three hundred people threw rocks and gas bombs at the building from outside. </seg>
<seg id="35"> The day before, student members of Iran's hard-line militia led hundreds of demonstrators in attacking the Danish and Austrian embassies in Tehran. </seg>
<seg id="36"> The controversial cartoons were first published by the Jutland Post in Denmark in September of last year. </seg>
<seg id="37"> They were successively reprinted in other European countries and three Arab newspapers. </seg>
<seg id="38"> In retaliation, Hamshahri, Iran's best-selling newspaper, recently announced that it would hold a contest on cartoons depicting the slaughter of Jews by the Nazi Germany. </seg>
<seg id="39"> The move was strongly denounced by the United States and other countries. </seg>
<seg id="40"> US State Department spokesman McCormack said that he thinks the move by the best-selling Iranian newspaper Hamshahri was to reinforce Iranian President Ahmadinejad's vicious anti-Israeli remarks. </seg>
<seg id="41"> McCormack reiterated the US support of freedom of speech in all parts of the world, including Iran. </seg>
<seg id="42"> But he thinks Hamshahri's cartoon contest was totally a different thing from the publication of the cartoons of Muhammad by the Danish media. </seg>
<seg id="43"> McCormack said, I don't think that someone will mention Iran's freedom of the press in connection with the freedom of the press in western Europe and the United States. </seg>
<seg id="44"> Ahmadinejad once called the Holocaust a myth and urged to wipe Israel off the map, setting off widespread criticism by the United States and other countries. </seg>
<seg id="45"> McCormack thinks that Hamshahri is funded by the conservative Tehran municipal government. </seg>
<seg id="46"> It was no coincidence that it should hold this cartoon contest. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="NTDTV_NTDNEWS19_CMN_20060215_185801_739_993.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> Since Attorney Gao Zhicheng initiated a coordinated 24-hour hunger strike campaign in ten cities across the country on February 14, protesting CPC persecution, recently another 170 Shanghai petitioners collectively signed on, expressing their willingness to participate in this human rights hunger strike. </seg>
<seg id="2"> In addition, they said they will continue to publicize the signatures and number of people in the second group of participants. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Next, let's take a look at an interview report by this station. </seg>
<seg id="4"> According to our understanding, under the government's intentional manipulation, real estate prices in Shanghai have become among the highest in the world. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Many government units think of all kinds of ways to forcibly tear down citizens' residences in high-priced neighborhoods without giving reasonable compensation. </seg>
<seg id="6"> These ordinary people who have suffered compulsory eviction, thereby losing their homes, have suddenly lost their sources of income. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Children are unable to pay tuition, and cannot attend school. </seg>
<seg id="8"> For many years, most people who appealed to higher authorities have been sent to reform-through-labor camps for long periods of time. </seg>
<seg id="9"> According to statistical data, Shanghai is the region of China with the largest number of people appealing to higher authorities. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Han Zhongming used to own a storefront, yet it was forcibly torn down.  His private residence was also sold by others for profit. </seg>
<seg id="11"> He was put under house arrest by authorities and was even detained because he appealed to higher authorities. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Having jumped from a building and slit his wrists, among other forms of protest, he was only recently released. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Chen Enjuan's storefront was also forcibly torn down by the government. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The government hired goons to drag her family of three out of their home and used bulldozers to raze the house together with the furniture. </seg>
<seg id="15"> She was sent to a reform-through-labor camp for nearly two years because she appealed to higher authorities. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Speaking about this hunger strike in support of the protest, Chen Enjuan said that besides it was for protesting against government iniquity, </seg>
<seg id="17"> Attorney Gao has also given us a lot of help and very unselfishly helped us. </seg>
<seg id="18"> We are safeguarding our rights because we want democracy, ah, because we are thinking of the next generation. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Our older generation has suffered enough.  We also need to make sure that the next generation will not suffer persecution.  That is why we want to participate in that human rights campaign.  We cannot give up. </seg>
<seg id="20"> According to the Center on Housing Rights and Evictions, a Geneva-based human rights organization, China has been listed among countries with the most serious housing rights violations in the world. </seg>
<seg id="21"> This has been an interview report by NTD News correspondent Wang Xin and guest reporter Gu Qing'er. </seg>
<seg id="22"> In response to the new round of human rights hunger strike campaign initiated by Attorney Gao Zhicheng, many democracy activists and ordinary citizens in Hong Kong, Taiwan, Calgary, Canada, and the greater Philadelphia area in the United States continued to voice their support in various forms on February 15. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The following is a comprehensive report by this station's correspodnent. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Based on the 24-hour coordinated hunger strike campaign in ten provinces and cities across China on February 14 initiated by Attorney Gao Zhicheng to protest CPC tyranny, a signature drive has been launched on the streets of Hong Kong. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Legislator Leung Kwok-hung, who supports Attorney Gao Zhicheng's hunger strike campaign, said that CPC authorities recently have made reckless arrests of human rights activists, which is a dangerous signal showing that this government is absolutely not based on popular will. </seg>
