<seg id="16"> On another note, the Georgian parliament's Defense and Security Committee held an expanded meeting and decided to expel the Russian peacekeeping force from South Ossetia. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The Russian parliament will hold a general assembly to review this bill today. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Er, experts think that if the parliament agrees to expel the Russian peacekeeping force, it may lead to the complete breakup of Georgian-Russian ties. </seg>
<seg id="19"> A spokesperson for the Russian peacekeeping force said on the 14th that two of the Russian peacekeeping contingent's military vehicles transporting foods were intercepted by Georgian police with the driver expelled. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Er, the spokesperson called for Georgia to stop immediately such provocations; otherwise Russia would assume no responsibility for the consequences of the incident. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Two military vehicles belonging to the logistic system of the Russian peacekeeping contingent transporting foods and groceries were examined by Georgian police Monday night in Georgia's South Ossetia. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Georgian law enforcement personnel on duty expelled the Russian driver and escorting personnel and forcibly drove away the two military vehicles. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The incident greatly angered the Russian peacekeeping force. </seg>
<seg id="24"> A spokesperson for the Russian peacekeeping force said that on February 1, Georgian police detained a Russian military vehicle in the area on an excuse of a traffic accident and has not returned it so far. </seg>
<seg id="25"> On February 8, three Russian military officers were detained for two days and nights on grounds of visa problems. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Georgia's reckless provocations were aimed to incur bloodshed in the area by forcing the Russian troops to open fire so that it could achieve the goal of the withdrawal of the peacekeeping force from South Ossetia. </seg>
<seg id="27"> On that day, the Russian embassy in Georgia made serious representations to the Georgian side, demanding Georgia to immediately stop frenzied provocations; otherwise the Russian side will not assume any consequence of the resulting conflict. </seg>
<seg id="28"> The media noted that on February 13, Georgian Defense Minister Okruashvili announced that the head of the Russian military base in Akhalkalaki sold several Strela portable air defense missile systems to South Ossetia. </seg>
<seg id="29"> On that day, the Georgian parliament Defense and Security Committee held an expanded meeting to hear a report by the law enforcement agency.  It decided to expel the Russian peacekeeping troops in Georgia and called for a review of this issue at the general assembly on the 14th. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Experts think that the final decision, once passed, may eventually lead to the complete breakup of Georgian-Russian ties. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Earlier, Georgian Foreign Minister Bezhuashvili vehemently criticized the Russian position and refuted Russian President Putin's remark that Russia may recognize Abkhazia and South Ossetia should the West recognize Kosovo.  He thinks that Russian authorities are sending an encouraging signal to all secessionist districts. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The Russian Foreign Ministry also announced earlier that it would protect Russian citizens in South Ossetia, implying a direct threat of military force to Georgia. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Lu Yuguang reporting from Moscow for Phoenix Satellite TV. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PHOENIX_GOODMORNCN_CMN_20060215_185801_1425_1568.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chf">
<seg id="1"> US Pacific Fleet Commander Roughead announced on Tuesday that this summer the United States will deploy four aircraft carriers to conduct the largest-ever military exercise in the Asia-Pacific region in ten years. </seg>
<seg id="2"> Roughead also said that the United States will, er, not consider, um, China, ah, a threat. </seg>
<seg id="3"> The US military is hoping to have another joint exercise with China's PLA Navy. </seg>
<seg id="4"> This declaration of position immediately drew the attention of US defense experts. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Heritage Foundation, a US think tank, held a forum on the Pentagon defense review report on Wednesday. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The subtle relationship between the defense report and the military exercise has become one of the focuses of discussion. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Some, however, think that Roughead's open invitation of China to participate in the military exercise was a sign of US friendship to China. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Since the US military also expressed hope for more transparency in China's PLA operations while inviting China to participate in the military exercise, some defense experts think that this shows the Pentagon's hope to sound each other out through the joint military exercise because it is not sure about the purpose of China's military expansion. </seg>
<seg id="9"> In addition, since the defense review report released by the Pentagon at the beginning of this month considered China the greatest potential threat, the two defense experts also pointed out that the Asia-Pacific military exercise is the first step that the US Department of Defense takes to adjust its strategy on this basis. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Xie Xiaoshuang reporting from Washington for Phoenix Satellite TV. </seg>
<seg id="11"> In addition, this time, this US military exercise in summer is drawing quite a lot of attention, because this is also, ah, the first time in a decade that the US has four aircraft carriers, ah, to participate jointly in a military exercise.  It is also the first time after the Vietnam War that the US deployed the aircraft carriers off the East Coast to do such a military exercise in this west Pacific Ocean region. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Well, this military exercise, ah, is actually very frequent, taking place four times in a few months. </seg>
