<DOC docid="groups.google.com_goodarticles_90837c9a1fbe858e_CMN_20060214_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Military Situation Observation: How Long can Iran Hold Up under Air Attacks by US Armed Forces? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> If traditional warfare of attrition is described as letting an opponent bleed to death, then modern warfare is shooting at the head of an opponent first and making him a "human vegetable" before he bleeds. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The gap between the military capabilities of Iran and the United States is not their quantities, but understanding of modern warfare. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Iran, which came to a draw with Iraq in an eight-year war, does not seem to understand the real meaning of modern high-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The British International Intelligence Comments pointed out a few days ago, after it analyzed the state of US armed forces movements, that the US armed forces are preparing to launch large-scale air attacks on Iran... </seg>
<seg id="7"> The current status of the Iranian air force is worrisome. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The present status of the Iranian air forces is quite similar with that of the Iraqi air force before the Iraq War in 2003. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Iran itself does not have the capacity to independently develop modern weapons, and is embargoed from importing weapons from the West. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Once a war breaks out, it is really a question of whether those old and obsolete aircrafts of the Iranian air force could take off to confront the US armed forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Currently, the Iranian air defense system is mainly composed of the air force and ground air defense troops of the Iranian regular armed forces, and the air-defense forces of the Revolutionary Guard Corps. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Among them, the Iranian air forces have around 50,000 troops, and more than 300 various types of combat aircrafts. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Their primary aircraft models include the F-4 "Phantom," F-5 "Tiger," and F-14 "Tomcat" made by the US and the MIG-29 made by Russia, etc. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The ground air defense troops are mainly equipped with surface to air missiles, including the US "Hawk," British "Javelin" and some of the Russian "SAM" series of missiles. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Harold Hutchinson, a US military expert, and Helamuchisin, a military expert from Russia's Politics and Military Analysis Institute, analyzed the current status of the Iranian air defense forces, and think that the Iranian air defense capacities and air defense system and construction still have some loopholes in the current status. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Hutchinson thinks that the Iranian air forces are not at all at the same level with the US armed forces from the perspective of whole actual strength. </seg>
<seg id="17"> A lot of the Iranian combat aircrafts made by the US cannot be used because of lack of parts, upgrades, and maintenance. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The F-14 fighter planes previously regarded as the elite ones in the Iranian air force only have about ten capable of taking off from the ground. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The combat reliability of AIM 54 "Phoenix" missiles, claimed to be capable of over-the-horizon attacks, is also doubtful. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Helamuchisin pointed out that those Iranian air defense missile systems provided by the US from the 1970s to the 1980s of the last century have lost their combat powers because of lack of spare parts. </seg>
<seg id="21"> And other air defense weapons that do not form any systems, such as weapons obtained from Russia and other countries, have no capabilities at all to cope with the US armed forces, which have powerful electromagnetic combat capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Scrappy weapons affect combat power </seg>
<seg id="23"> Apparently, the Iranian government realizes that its fate in a war depends on whether it is capable of defending the sky over its head, and is starting to prepare only at the last moment, scrape weapons together, and strengthen its air defense system. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Its methods can be summed up as the two strategies from the current state: </seg>
<seg id="25"> The first one is to conceal important nuclear facilities as much as possible and strengthen their anti-strike capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="26"> According to a report from the British newspaper Times, Iran has hidden core parts of its nuclear facilities 18 meters under ground and added a protection shell of 2-meter-thick cement, including the nuclear plant in Natanz and the uranium enrichment center in Isfahan. </seg>
<seg id="27"> But the US armed forces have taken a strategy in advance. They saw the effects of underground bunkers in anti-air attack combat as early as during the Gulf War in 1991, and have rushed developing various ground-penetrating bombs. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Through more than 10 years' studies on targets, the US armed forces have had a whole set of combat methods and weapons coping with underground consolidated bunkers. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Iran has also purchased a lot of advanced air defense weapons from Russia in recent years. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Since the end of last year, the Iranian government has reached agreements with Russia, one after another, for the purchase of the Pechora-2A air defense missile system and 29 sets of "Dower" air defense missile systems, worth 700 million US dollars. </seg>
<seg id="31"> However, a modern war is a rivalry between systems. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Various US armed forces air-attack weapons are developed by the US itself, and they have been sharpened and become a set of war machines with outstanding effects after years of tests in actual warfare. </seg>
<seg id="33"> And those "new weapons" scraped together by Iran from other countries are still a question of whether they can form combat power in a short time. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Weapons are not Iran's only gap. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Combat Outlines, published by the US armed forces in 1982, first came up with the idea of "integrated air-ground warfare," and stressed the use of air supremacy to strike high-value targets in an enemy's strategic depth area, paralyzing the enemy's command system at the beginning of a war, and making him as "meat on the cutting board" even though he has very powerful conventional forces. </seg>
<seg id="36"> In the Gulf War in 1991, Kosovo War in 1999, and the Iraq War in 2003, what the US armed forces paid attention to was not how many aircrafts the opponents had, but the firing range of their own "Tomahawk" cruise missile. </seg>
<seg id="37"> Although the Iranian government has prepared for possible air attacks and started to take measures to strengthen air defense capabilities, Iran, which came to a draw with Iraq in an eight-year war, does not seem to understand the real meaning of modern high-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="38"> With the development of US armed forces military transition work in recent years, the air-attack activities of the US armed forces are totally different from the carpet bombing method in the Vietnam War era, and rely on various new high-tech weapons and high-precision and whole-depth air strikes that are based on modern information technology. </seg>
<seg id="39"> How long the Iranian ground air defense system can sustain itself in this kind of air strikes is still an unknown element. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Source: international online- World News Journal </seg>
