<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_05a0a5b917a9b705_CMN_20060208_063400" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Xu Zhiyong: A Letter to Li Qun, the Secretary of Linyi City Party Committee </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER> Fa Buer </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Sender: sunnypku (sunny) </seg>
<seg id="4"> Mail area: square </seg>
<seg id="5"> Title: Xu Zhiyong: A Letter to Li Qun, the Secretary of Linyi City Party Committee: Hooliganism will Also Harm Yourself </seg>
<seg id="6"> Website for sending mail: Feeling Like Old Friends at the First Meeting (Wed Feb 8 13:56:14 2006). This website (yjrg.net) </seg>
<seg id="7"> Until yesterday, the government of Linyi, led by you, had illegally placed Chen Guangcheng under house arrest for 165 days. </seg>
<seg id="8"> You collaborated with rogues and the mafia society to put a blind legal citizen in jail illegally for a long time. </seg>
<seg id="9"> You cut off his home's phone line, installed a cell phone jamming device in his yard; </seg>
<seg id="10"> You also beat him and his family members many times. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Your barbarous conduct has gone beyond the bottom line of a civilized society. </seg>
<seg id="12"> You also used means of rogues and the mafia society to beat me and lawyer Li Fangping in the beginning of October, 2005. But we bore this, and we always tried to understand your difficult situation as much as possible, and were even acquiescent for a time of the house arrest of Chen Guangcheng. </seg>
<seg id="13"> However, 165 days have passed. You not only have not controlled your behavior, but you also make it worse. </seg>
<seg id="14"> You sent a big team of policemen and rogues to harass villagers; </seg>
<seg id="15"> You continued to arrest and beat villagers; </seg>
<seg id="16"> What you have done is too outrageous! </seg>
<seg id="17"> Today, I clearly remind you that those means of rogues and the mafia society will harm yourself in turn at the moment when you continue to organize rogues and the mafia society to besiege Chen Guangcheng. </seg>
<seg id="18"> It was worth your examination when this thing started in the beginning. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The family planning of Linyi is the first one from the bottom of the provincial list in the whole province. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The anxiety in your mind is understandable as the secretary of the city Party committee. </seg>
<seg id="21"> But it is wrong for you to think that only use of violence and force can implement the state's law and policy because of the low qualities of the people in Linyi. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Whose fault exactly is it that citizens do not coordinate with the conduct of the government? </seg>
<seg id="23"> Is it because of the low qualities of the citizens or much less public trust, since the government has told too many lies and made too many schemes? </seg>
<seg id="24"> If (we) say that the same government's conduct was not that absurd ten years ago, in 2005 China's society has made obvious progress and human rights protection has been written into the Constitution; don't you think that your barbarous conduct is too outrageous? </seg>
<seg id="25"> Why don't you examine that only your Linyi dares to act in this way? </seg>
<seg id="26"> Why is only your Linyi unable to practice law enforcement by using democratic and legal means? </seg>
<seg id="27"> Linyi City should have been able to make a sincere explanation and make the public understand, after a batch of brave citizens including Chen Guangcheng reported about the fact of the barbarous law enforcement, a batch of citizens including Teng Biao - who dared to protect citizen's rights - were involved, and the investigation conclusion was made by the National Family Planning Committee. </seg>
<seg id="28"> After all, family planning is a difficult topic with Chinese characteristics. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Everyone can understand your difficulties. </seg>
<seg id="30"> However, you took a further absurd measure - brought Chen Guangcheng back and put him in jail by catching him from Beijing - and also tried to accuse him of illegally providing the state's confidential information. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Don't you think that it is a very absurd accusation for a blind man who lives in a poor mountain village? </seg>
<seg id="32"> In fact, as long as you have truly corrected mistakes, as long as you have done things very well, are you still afraid of the criticism of a blind man? </seg>
<seg id="33"> Is it necessary for you to send several dozens of people to watch him 24 hours a day, and even sentence him in a hurried and desperate way? </seg>
<seg id="34"> I and Lawyer Li Fangping arrived in Dongshigu Village on October 4, 2005. We demonstrated our very clear position and hoped to solve the conflicts. </seg>
<seg id="35"> We made a suggestion that we could talk with your officials to learn your ideas and requests. </seg>
<seg id="36"> We took the initiative and suggested that we could help you to persuade Chen Guangcheng, to influence him not to say some of his words. </seg>
<seg id="37"> We hoped that you would not treat a blind man in this way, and both sides should make some compromises. </seg>
<seg id="38"> However, your decision maker just follow his own way, and moreover, even had "carefully planned" an episode - to beat and put us in jail illegally. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Do you think that your activities can make us scared? </seg>
<seg id="40"> We have not done anything that violates laws. </seg>
<seg id="41"> We are fearless. </seg>
<seg id="42"> Although China's legal system is not perfect, at least it has not become absolutely lawless. </seg>
<seg id="43"> You think that use of means of rogues and the mafia society can scare us away, then you have greatly underestimated our determination and willpower. </seg>
<seg id="44"> As long as we would like to, we have many people who have many legitimate reasons to go to Linyi or go to see Chen Guangcheng. </seg>
<seg id="45"> You can beat lawyers and scholars one, two, and three times, but every time would attract broad attention and reports about it. </seg>
<seg id="46"> Do you really dare to beat us ten times? </seg>
<seg id="47"> Don't you care about your official position very much? </seg>
<seg id="48"> If somebody is beaten and injured, will your position still be in a solid status? </seg>
<seg id="49"> Not listening to our reasonable advice, instead using some indecent means of rogues, don't you think this is very silly and dangerous? </seg>
<seg id="50"> I want to tell you clearly that, in China, there is a big batch of excellent citizens who are loyal to conscience and follow the legal system. </seg>
<seg id="51"> We do not fear rogues and the mafia society. </seg>
<seg id="52"> We cannot stand reckless trampling on the bottom line of human civilization. </seg>
<seg id="53"> If you have done too much beyond boundaries, we will calmly and confidently march forward batch by batch toward your sticks until the moment when you retreat. </seg>
<seg id="54"> You should be clear that use of the means of rogues and the mafia society is not something good for you. </seg>
<seg id="55"> Do not think that you can get rid of any link connected with those local rogues or hooligans who beat villagers as long as you hide backstage. </seg>
<seg id="56"> Finally, I also want to remind you to treat Chen Guangcheng well. </seg>
<seg id="57"> A person who was blind from his childhood, graduated from a college of traditional Chinese medicine, self-studied laws and English, and sued Beijing Subway Company for the interest of the blind, and brought tap water for villagers, and became a well-known "Lawyer Chen" everywhere. </seg>
<seg id="58"> You even mobilized shameful indecent individuals to make rumors about and slander him, and tried to accuse him of illegally sending confidential information across the border. Don't you think that what you did is too outrageous? </seg>
<seg id="59"> It is illegal for you to place Chen Guangcheng under house arrest, and it is also dangerous for you to do this. </seg>
<seg id="60"> You should have been able to release him for sure. </seg>
<seg id="61"> If the conduct of barbarous law enforcement has been stopped, how long could he maintain the criticism if you let him criticize it freely? </seg>
<seg id="62"> But today you are continuously smearing your own image. </seg>
<seg id="63"> You won't be peaceful as long as Chen Guangcheng has not been set for free for a day. </seg>
<seg id="64"> It is enough for you to make him suffer. </seg>
<seg id="65"> We would never stand by and do nothing if you still want to charge him with any crime or use further rogue means. </seg>
<seg id="66"> Citizen Xu Zhiyong, February 8, 2006 </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_6053475d4e68ca65_CMN_20060217_101400" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Does the Chinese Nation Deserve to Have Democracy? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER> Exploration of the path of China's peace and liberation, and promotion of the ideological liberation of our countrymen </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I admit very disappointedly that the Chinese nation does not deserve to have democracy!!! </seg>
<seg id="4"> Aren't those who post their messages here doing this thing now! </seg>
<seg id="5"> The pity is that there are not many people who go online and read it (compared with 1.4 billion). </seg>
<seg id="6"> Those who go online and care and participate in these kinds of topics would be much fewer: I dare to allege that the number would be less than 1% of people online. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Not to mention that this network has the Golden Shield project, which is the biggest, most thorough, advanced, expensive, and quality one. </seg>
<seg id="8"> It is true. </seg>
<seg id="9"> One could feel depressed, hopeless, helpless, and even think of surrendering, but if one wants to live a human life, whom can he depend on except that he himself struggles for it? </seg>
<seg id="10"> Although doing a thing depends on human effort, and success relies on the Heavens, I would think I am wrong if I have not made an effort for my own ideal, even though it is not successful, and I deserve to live like a dog. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Making an effort for a just thing itself can make one's own life somewhat wonderful, and at least in his heart when he evaluates himself. </seg>
<seg id="12"> In fact, I do not need to be concerned about China's future at all, </seg>
<seg id="13"> because the environment in the world is no longer allowing a regime that has not been elected to exist for long. </seg>
<seg id="14"> This is just a matter of time. </seg>
<seg id="15"> What I lament is that the Chinese nation is very lucky to be led on the path to hell by a world-class great man and completely exploited from its bone and blood whenever it is at a historical turning point. Even if somebody calls piles of white bones and areas of blood stains along the path as brilliances, and forces us to be proud of the brilliances. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Everywhere has a dark night, but the longest one is in Shenzhou (the sacred state). </seg>
<seg id="17"> People would suffer a lot when the Qin Emperor integrated with the Confucian Sage. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Qin Shihuang was an open tyranny and the Confucian Sage privately washed brains. </seg>
<seg id="19"> It is not that Chinese people do not deserve to have democracy; it is because they have not had the democratic gene or their gene has been degenerated. </seg>
<seg id="20"> A nation that has been established for more than three thousand years, it might have had democracy a long time ago if its national culture contained democratic elements. </seg>
<seg id="21"> What were Chinese people doing when Athens established a democratic system, Rome set up a republic, the British passed the Constitution, the French published the Declaration of Human Rights, and the Americans issued the Declaration of Independence? </seg>
<seg id="22"> Mongolians had a Kurultai system for selection of their king before they entered into Zhong Yuan; Manchurians in their early time had a Ministers Council of the Prince Regent for democratic consultation. Why were those systems all gone when they entered into the Han region? </seg>
<seg id="23"> Chinese people pursue materials only and have no interest in spiritual faith and political rights. </seg>
<seg id="24"> If you do not believe it, as long as a Chinese person has an election right, he can sell it to you for a meat pancake. </seg>
<seg id="25"> 500,000 years later, if Chinese people want democracy, there must be an earthquake coming. If you can run, please do it! </seg>
<seg id="26"> Posted via news://freenews.netfront.net </seg>
<seg id="27"> Complaints to n ... @netfront.net </seg>
<seg id="28"> Oh, oh, it is a very well written one, but cannot wake up ignorant Chinese people. </seg>
<seg id="29"> &quot;jack&quot;&lt;mskaizp ... @hotmail.com&gt; </seg>
<seg id="30"> Written into news: dssi2r$2ql ... @adenine.netfront.net... </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_a6b18a4b27644df8_CMN_20060215_083500" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Dalai Envoy Holding Closed-Door Meeting with Chinese Officials </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dalai Envoy Holding Closed-Door Meeting with Chinese Officials </seg>
<seg id="4"> The Dalai Lama stressed that he hopes that Tibet will have autonomy instead of independence. </seg>
<seg id="5"> An envoy of the Dalai Lama, the Tibetan spiritual leader in exile, is holding a closed-door meeting with Chinese officials in Beijing, and no details have been disclosed publicly. </seg>
<seg id="6"> This is the fifth formal meeting since China and the Dalai government in exile restored their contact in 2002. </seg>
<seg id="7"> But as usual, neither side has disclosed any details when holding the closed-door meeting. </seg>
<seg id="8"> A reporter said that both sides have held many talks, but have not made any substantial achievement so far. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Dalai Lama, who is in exile in North India, said that he hopes that Tibet will have autonomy instead of independence. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The Chinese side refused to make any comment on the bilateral talks. </seg>
<seg id="11"> But as analysts said, the reason why Beijing hoped to have the bilateral talks is partially because it is worried that if the spiritual leader in exile dies, it might make Tibetans unhappier about China's rule. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Cultural identification </seg>
<seg id="13"> The Dalai government in exile delegation is led by Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari, who was the chief delegate for several previous talks. </seg>
<seg id="14"> A spokesman for the Tibetan government in exile said that several talks held in Switzerland between them and Chinese officials in 2005 were very "close and frank," which brings hope to Tibetans. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The spokesman said that they hope to eventually solve related issues with the Chinese leadership based on the foundation established by negotiations, and let the Tibetans have freedom, and maintain the cultural identification that they think is the most important thing. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="16"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="17"> Dalai Lama Envoy Reiterated not to Seek Tibetan Independence. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The Dalai Lama will visit Washington DC this month. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Before the Dalai Lama, the Tibetan spiritual leader, visits the United States on November 8, his envoy said that the Tibetan government in exile does not request Tibetan independence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said in Washington that he hopes that the Chinese government will ensure protection of the unique Tibetan culture and tradition. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is expected that when the Dalai Lama visits the United States next week, he will discuss Tibetan issues with President Bush, and hope that Bush could urge the Chinese government to give Tibet real autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Delegates of the Dalai and officials from Beijing had direct contact for the first time in Bern in July of this year. </seg>
<seg id="23"> "A Real Autonomy" </seg>
<seg id="24"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari pointed out that both the Tibetan government in exile and Chinese authorities have seen some positive aspects from their talks in recent years. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Dalai Lama's envoy discovered that leaders from Beijing, especially those delegates of the Central United Front Work Department of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, are more willing to listen to their views than they did before. </seg>
<seg id="26"> However, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that there are too many differences between the Tibetan government in exile and the Chinese government, and there is a big gap between the positions of both sides. </seg>
<seg id="27"> He said that in the past five years, the Tibetan government in exile has done its best to create a good environment for negotiation requested by China, </seg>
<seg id="28"> and China should also create a good environment for negotiation of the Tibetan issue, and should not suppress the Dalai Lama all the time. </seg>
<seg id="29"> He said that the Dalai Lama does not request Tibetan independence, and Tibet is still a part of China, but the Chinese government must maintain the unique culture of Tibet and "let Tibetans have a real autonomy." </seg>
<seg id="30"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari also pointed out that some Chinese think that as soon as the Dalai Lama passes away, the Tibetan issue will disappear. </seg>
<seg id="31"> He said that this view is very dangerous, because once the Dalai Lama is gone, China would lose the historical opportunity to solve the Tibetan issue. </seg>
<seg id="32"> He said that as long as the Chinese government responds to the request raised by the Dalai Lama, and comes up with a final solution, the Dalai Lama would not need to talk about the Tibetan issue internationally any more. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b07aeae684cbc1b7_CMN_20060209_051800" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Negotiation and Compromise are the Important Means of Democracy! (ZT) </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I just now saw a poster on "Great Decency -To Old Mr. Guiren" sent by a network friend. </seg>
<seg id="4"> His (her) original words are that "Negotiation and compromise are the important means of democracy. Otherwise, a split because of different views is a failure of democracy!!! Hope that those ideal democrats pay fully attention to this!" </seg>
<seg id="5"> This plain and tasteless sentence, which has not attracted interest from any network friends, has made me imagine a lot and have many sorts of feelings. </seg>
<seg id="6"> At that moment I thought of the ancient times of China and the past of the West. </seg>
<seg id="7"> I seldom sent the main poster. I cannot help but reply to the poster of the network friend in the way of the main poster. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Let's see China's ancient times. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Everyone knows that since Qin Shihuang established the universally unified and centralized power system in China, any subsequent dynasties were operated under the political framework. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Although the Han Dynasty temporarily implemented a "two-track system," i.e. a political system that practiced the feudal system and centralized power system at the same time, it eventually switched to a complete centralized power system in the end. </seg>
<seg id="11"> The outcome of this kind of centralized power system had an advanced aspect in the historical condition by then, which promoted the development of productivity. </seg>
<seg id="12"> But we should also see that the long-term operation of the system for more than 2,000 years had made local administrations lacking of their creativities, initiatives, and enthusiasms, and unable to make various suitable systems and policies for local developments based on local circumstances. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The pyramid type of ruling system had made lower-class officials looking upward only and following directions from their superiors for everything. </seg>
<seg id="14"> There was no room for coordination and negotiation because even local officials at the county level were appointed by the central government, not to mention those common people. </seg>
<seg id="15"> When rights of farmers were infringed upon in ancient China, they could only bear it time and again. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Only when their basest rights were threatened, i.e. when a famine spread in big areas, a tyrannical rule or natural disaster caused loss of their living rights, would they rebel. </seg>
<seg id="17"> In more than 2,000 years, many peasant uprisings spread everywhere in the country like storms, but they never won a victory in a real sense except Zhu Yuanzhang, from Chen Sheng, and Wu Guang, who did not plan their uprising to the planned Huang Jin Insurrection, from the Huang Chao Revolt in the Tang Dynasty to the Li Zhicheng Rebellion that established a dynasty for only a month. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Even the Ming Dynasty created by Zhu Yuanzhang was only a cycle of other dynasties, and there were no systematic changes. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Zhu Yuanzhang, who came from a common family and did not receive much education, played the Chinese ancient centralized power system to a sick extent, and to extremes. Since then, the vigorous state of the type of the Tang Dynasty that was open, free, and tolerant, had become depressed. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The atmosphere of freedom of speech disappeared in the vast land of China for a time. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Human nature was suppressed to the maximum extent. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Everybody became very cautious and dared not to say more words with reverence and awe. </seg>
<seg id="23"> This was the only outcome of peasant uprisings in 2,000 years, and it made Chinese people neither humans nor ghosts. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Let's see the Medieval Ages of the so-called dark time in Western Europe. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Medieval Ages of Western Europe were formed after the Western Rome was destroyed by nomadic nations, and lasted for a thousand years. They had nothing to do with the ancient Greece and Rome of the past. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Those ages featured the feudal system, i.e. land holding. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Many layers of land feudal lords, from the top to the bottom, had more autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="28"> No matter whether small feudal lords who had an area of several square kilometers, or nobles who had titles of Duke, Marquis, Count, Viscount, and Baron, since superiors and inferiors, and the left and right, could balance, restrain, and were interdependent with each other, and had their prerequisites and capabilities to strive for their own rights against kings, the scenes in which nobles sat with a king negotiating for their own interest emerged, which never happened in China's ancient times. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Compromises and concessions were made mutually instead use of violent means to knock down or replace opponents. </seg>
<seg id="30"> In this way, through making various contracts, rights were continuously transferred to nobles and common people, and they had more and more rights, and kings had fewer and fewer. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Later, the British Queen had only a status for display, and not any substantial power. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Democracy was gradually realized in this way! </seg>
<seg id="33"> Let's come back again to compare with ancient China, where every power was concentrated in the hands of emperors (except Li Shimin), and there were almost no nobles. It was very difficult for peasants to be able to sit in front of a negotiation table, joyfully making compromises and concessions on a contract agreed to by both sides while enjoying a cup of tea or a glass of wine. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Under this circumstance, when the living right was taken away, only violent means could overthrow an existing dynasty and try to replace it. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Its outcome was the repeated cycle from the peak of the Tang Dynasty to the sick status of the Ming Dynasty. </seg>
<seg id="36"> Comparing histories between China and the West, we discovered that the contradictions between rulers and the ruled in ancient China were much more intensified than those in ancient Western countries. </seg>
<seg id="37"> No Western countries had so many continuous peasant uprisings as ancient China had. </seg>
<seg id="38"> In the Western countries, when differences between ancient royal families and peasants emerged, what nobles and common people thought of first was to settle them through a negotiation path, to obtain more rights gradually by making mutual concessions, and they seldom used violent means. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Understanding this, when we enter into the 21st century, we can still see those democratic warriors in networks who have inherited the ideology of the absolute power concentration system of the Ming Dynasty, </seg>
<seg id="40"> and have been poisoned by the virus of the Cultural Revolution that they can say nothing except those words of "Down with or overthrow something." </seg>
<seg id="41"> And those concepts are the biggest barrier to democracy, because those people do not understand that negotiation, coordination, and compromise are the most important means and path for realization of democracy. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b1314fab782e7592_CMN_20060209_044700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Cao Xiaoming: Who is Going to "Pay the Bill" for Enriching Cultural Activities in Rural Areas </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Hou Ze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> The author was lucky to spend this year's Spring Festival in a rural area of the Mainland, and visited some relatives and friends. </seg>
<seg id="4"> I was not only influenced by the dense atmosphere of the festival in the Chinese rural area, but also concerned about those boring cultural activities there. </seg>
<seg id="5"> The author discovered in a village where my relatives lived that this village organized villagers spontaneously to play a drama called "trotting horse lamp" for every Spring Festival in the past. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The drama is based on figures in the story of The Three Kingdoms. Any adult or child could play a role in the drama, and villagers were not bored at all to watch it a hundred times. </seg>
<seg id="7"> There were several of this kind of performance teams of "trotting horse lamp" in the whole township. They performed not only in their own villages, but also went to other villages for visits, and exchanged frequently. </seg>
<seg id="8"> But this village did not organize the performance this year. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The reason is that just the costumes for "trotting horse lamp" would cost a lot, which were bought in the past through donations from villagers. Now they are too worn out to be taken on. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Nobody was willing to donate any more, if asking villagers for donations household by household. Other villages in the township had a similar situation. </seg>
<seg id="11"> The village suddenly became quiet without the "trotting horse lamp." </seg>
<seg id="12"> Adults started to play Mahjong. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Children also began to play cards. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Villagers said that this festival had no fun. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The big scene in the countryside is either shooting off fireworks or playing Mahjong during the festival. </seg>
<seg id="16"> The gambling trend cannot be stopped even though it is prohibited time and again, and is spread even further. Gambling for up to ten thousand Yuan has become a routine game. Especially, big batches of those migrant farmer workers who come back to their hometowns from other areas have played major roles in gambling sites. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Their hard-earned money from working in other areas for a year is lost in this way. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Family disputes occurred time and again because of gambling, which sometimes causes tragedies with families broken up and decimated. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Some farmers said that they gambled not only during festivals but also participated in gambling frequently in slack seasons. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Nowhere to go if they did not gamble. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is too difficult to organize cultural activities and look for "fun" in the countryside. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Not only are there no facilities and funding, but also nobody organizes them. </seg>
<seg id="23"> But in this aspect, the practice in Jiangxi is definitely good news for farmers. </seg>
<seg id="24"> To enrich the cultural life of the farmer masses, the government of Jiangxi Province not only implemented the policy that "the government provides funding for it; the market operates it; townships build stages; and farmers watch dramas" last September, </seg>
<seg id="25"> but they also arranged at least 60 million Yuan every year for the special fund for rural cultural causes and delivered good-quality cultural products to the rural masses. </seg>
<seg id="26"> In the beginning of this New Year, it added an additional 40 million Yuan, a total of 100 million Yuan, for the establishment of special funding for the rural cultural cause. </seg>
<seg id="27"> And also, what this special funding "paid" toward the farmers' "bill" is quite a good deal: </seg>
<seg id="28"> Various professional performance organizations are invited to have shows in rural areas, and provide at least four shows for every town each year. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Movie companies at every level are invited to organize film projection teams to show movies in the countryside, and at least six feature or scientific education movies should be shown for every administrative village each year; </seg>
<seg id="30"> Cultural activities with local features participated in by the masses are organized and developed at least two to three times for every township each year. </seg>
<seg id="31"> It is not difficult for us to see from the "purchase list" that the government does not simply pay the bill, but thinks hard how to use the limited funds in the critical area and deliver a cultural banquet that exceeds its money value to the farmer masses, and has done a big substantial thing for them. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Now, a lot of farmers are very happy and joyful for immunity from providing "royal grains and state's tax." </seg>
<seg id="33"> If every government can pay the "bill" for enriching cultural activities of the farmer masses as Jiangxi did, it would be another happy thing falling from the sky for farmers. </seg>
<seg id="34"> And this "happy thing" can not only liberate farmers from the Mahjong table, and make them "active" in cultural activities, but also add bricks and tiles for the construction of the new socialist countryside. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_d6c87f9f9950da31_CMN_20060214_106700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chg">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> It Was a False Alarm that a Child of Wang Peirong Was Almost Hijacked </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> peirongwangsohu@gmail.com </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> It was a false alarm that a child of Wang Peirong was almost hijacked </seg>
<seg id="4"> The child of Wang Peirong recounted it completely at a little bit after 9 p.m. on the evening of January 24, 2006: </seg>
<seg id="5"> The child of Wang Peirong was called off by a gate guard when she was making up missed physics lessons at the Third Middle School of Xuzhou on the morning of January 24, 2006. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The guard said to Wang Peirong's child that three unidentified men had told the gate guard at the Third Middle School that Wang Tianjiao, the child of Wang Peirong, had not gone back home for three days because of discord between her parents. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Now her mother was missing, and they were leaders from her mother's work unit, and wanted to enter the Third Middle School and take away Wang Peirong's child. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Wang Peirong's child said: what the three men said was totally untrue. She refused to go with the three men. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Wang Peirong's child was not taken away with the help of the gate guard of the Third Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Wang Peirong's child called one of her mother's leaders at noontime to confirm it. The leader denied that he had sent his men to visit the Third Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Wang Peirong's child obtained a phone number of one of her father's leaders from her. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Wang Peirong's child called her father's leader. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Wang Peirong's child said: three men visited the Third Middle School and wanted to take me away. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The leader asked: why didn't you go with them? </seg>
<seg id="15"> Wang Peirong's child said: I would be dead for sure if I went with them. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Wang Peirong's child hung up the phone right away after she finished her words. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Wang Peirong felt that the case was serious after she listened to her child's description, and reported it to the police. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The feedback from a public security station on January 25 was that Wang Peirong's child's description was basically true. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The public security station asked the security unit of Kuangda if it had sent those men to look for Wang Peirong's child; the response was no. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The station asked the security unit again, and other units under Kuangda, if they had sent those men to look for Wang Peirong's child; their responses also were no. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Some related department passed on a message to Wang Peirong and her family members through another person, and asked them to pay attention to their security. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Leaders of some related department in Xuzhou City had paid close attention to the incident after it occurred. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The possibility of hijacking the child was excluded through an investigation done by the criminal detection unit of the Public Security Bureau of Xuzhou City. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Wang Peirong thanked leaders of related departments in Xuzhou City and the criminal detection unit of the Public Security Bureau of Xuzhou City. </seg>
<seg id="25"> This was a false alarm that was probably mainly caused by the gate guard at the Third Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Now the criminal detection unit of the Public Security Bureau of Xuzhou City finds out that, on January 24, three men, including leaders of the work unit of the Physics Institute where Wang Peirong works, called Wang Peirong, but could not find her (Wang Peirong still does not know what for so far). They tried to find Wang Peirong in a hurry and wanted to look for a teacher of Wang Peirong's child to ask if Wang Peirong's child was still in Xuzhou or not. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Heavy talking topic: why corruption has a lower risk but anti-corruption has a higher cost </seg>
<seg id="28">  http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&amp;typeid=39 </seg>
<seg id="29"> What a corrupted official cares about is those several related officials who are his superiors in the current cadre and anti-corruption mechanisms, not the masses of people. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Thus, once he feels that he has successfully deceived or tamed those several officials who can determine his fate, he would boldly do whatever he likes to conduct his great cause for accumulation of wealth through corruption, and could ignore the feelings of the masses of people that are only a few feet away from them. </seg>
<seg id="31"> On the contrary, if common people who do not have power in their hands take the initiative to oppose corruption, they might bring extremely brutal strikes and retaliation upon themselves, </seg>
<seg id="32"> or be imposed with political accusations, and end up with failure before achieving any victory. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Compared with the two sides, corrupted individuals have lower risk, but individuals who oppose corruption have to bear a higher cost. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Please read the Webpage for the whole text: http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&typeid=39 </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060207_145800_396_582.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chh">
<seg id="1"> We now turn our attention once again to the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) confirmed on the 6th that the Iranian government had sent a letter to the IAEA requiring the removal before the middle of the month of all devices monitoring Iranian nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Due to the IAEA's decision to report the Iranian nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, Iran has declared a halt to all supportive and cooperative measures taken in regards to the nuclear issue and said it would no longer authorize the IAEA to make surprise checks of its nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Addressing the current tension over the Iranian nuclear issue, Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov said in Athens, Greece that that Russian-Iranian cooperation was ongoing. </seg>
<seg id="5"> And that it would become the motive force for a solution to the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="6"> On the same day, a  Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs spokesman said that Russia's proposal to Iran about setting up a joint venture in Russia for enriching uranium was still valid. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The two sides may discuss the issue next week. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The same day, US Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Lugar said at UN headquarters in New York that the US does not approve of an Israeli attack on Iranian nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Recently, Israeli defense experts were reported as saying that, if necessary, the Israeli air force may heavily damage Iran's nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="10"> According to Xinhua News Agency， Russian Vice Foreign Minister Kyslyak said on the 7th that Russia is willing to cooperate with Iran on the nuclear issue and help Iran obtain lawful power for the peaceful development of nuclear energy. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Kyslyak said that Russia's proposal about launching a joint venture for enriching uranium with Iran is still open. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Russia hopes to consult with Iran regarding the issue soon. </seg>
<seg id="13"> In late December last year, Russia delivered a proposal to Iran regarding the establishment of a joint venture for enriching uranium in Russia. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Both the EU and the US agreed that the plan was an acceptable compromise. </seg>
<seg id="15"> But Iran wants Russia to continue to revise the original plan. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs Spokesman Kong Quan said on the 7th that although the IAEA reported the Iranian nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, the organization's responsibility for settling the issue has not been passed on to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Therefore, the parties concerned should still try to break the deadlock over the issue within the framework of IAEA. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Under an IAEA resolution, IAEA Director General El Baradei will deliver a report on the Iranian nuclear issue to the Security Council in March. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The Security Council will make a final decision after evaluating the report. </seg>
<seg id="20"> We believe that such a resolution, it talks about requiring the Iranians...well ... being able to implement the relevant resolutions of the Security Council and honor their commitments. Besides, it does not deliver the issue or pass it on to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Recently, China has been seeking a plan for the peaceful resolution of the Iranian nuclear issue through diplomatic channels. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Kong Quan said that on February 1, Zhang Yan, Director of the Department of Armament Control for China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, met in Tehran with Ali Larijani, Secretary of Iran's Supreme National Security Council and Iran's chief nuclear negotiator, for talks on the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="23"> China hopes that Iran should take full note of the concern of the international community and create conditions for the peaceful solution of the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="24"> A solution for the Iranian nuclear issue within IAEA framework is not only in the interest of China. We firmly believe that it is also in the interest of all parties. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Therefore, we again appeal to the concerned parties in the international community not to abandon diplomatic efforts in respect to the issue. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060208_145800_256_429.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chh">
<seg id="1"> Hamas, which is in the process of organizing a new Palestine autonomous government, officially announced that, with the exception of choice for prime minister, the list of cabinet members in the new government is essentially in order. </seg>
<seg id="2"> This triggered speculations among outsiders regarding the choice for the prime minister. </seg>
<seg id="3"> On the 8th, a senior Hamas official revealed to the Associated Press that Hamas intends to nominate Al-Khudairi , board chairman of Gaza's Islamic University (and a merchant), as prime minister of the new autonomous government, but the nomination has not yet been formally delivered to Abbas. </seg>
<seg id="4"> With the support of Hamas, 50-year-old Al-Khudairi took part in the election of Palestinian Legislative Council held last month in the capacity of independent candidate. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Al-Khudairi has never mentioned violence or anti-Israeli content in his open speeches. </seg>
<seg id="6"> But he once indicated that Palestine was in need of internal reform. </seg>
<seg id="7"> A senior delegation from Hamas is now visiting Cairo to discuss with Egypt issues related to the formation of a new Palestinian government by Hamas. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Khaled Mashaal, a delegation member, told the press on the 8th that although the international community and some Arab countries have been exerting constant pressure, the Palestinian government formed under the leadership of Hamas will not recognize Israel. </seg>
<seg id="9"> At the same time, Mashaal also warned Abbas in his speech not to take the liberty of changing the structure of the Palestinian leadership without first consulting with Hamas. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Analysts believe that this is a response to the intention of Abbas to appoint Interior Minister Nasser Yousef as deputy commander of the security troops. </seg>
<seg id="11"> In reply to questions about the establishment of a new Palestinian autonomous government, Mashaal refused to confirm the news that Hamas plans to nominate Al-Khudairi, board chairman of the Islamic University in Gaza (and merchant) as prime minister. </seg>
