<seg id="1"> Now let's take a look at today's headlines. </seg>
<seg id="2"> A group of Chinese engineers and technicians were attacked by armed militants on the 15th in the province of Balochistan in the south of Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Of these, three engineers from Hefei, Anwei Province were killed. The Pakistani driver of the vehicle was also killed. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Local police described the incident as an open terrorist attack. </seg>
<seg id="5"> The Chinese consulate-general in Karachi has been consulting with the local government regarding necessary arrangements following the deaths. It has also asked the Pakistan authorities to apprehend the killers. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The group of engineers from China was working at a local cement plant. </seg>
<seg id="7"> They were sprayed with bullets on the 15th by a gunmen riding on the back of a motorcycle on a road in town of Hab, approximately 15km from Pakistan's largest city, Karachi. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Two died on the spot, while a third succumbed to heavy wounds later on. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Pakistani driver of the vehicle was also killed. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The three were all from the city of Hefei in Anwei province. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Three other Chinese traveling with them in the same vehicle survived with no injuries. </seg>
<seg id="12"> China's consulate-general in Karachi expressed its extreme concern over the incident. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Following the incident, we immediately sent our top-level diplomatic and consular officers to the worksite where the incident took place to...huh...assist in handling arrangements following the deaths. </seg>
<seg id="14"> We have moved all 11 of the remaining  technicians working on the project at the worksite to shelter in Karachi. </seg>
<seg id="15"> In addition, we have transported the remains of the three deceased compatriots to a hospital in Karachi for storage. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Uh...we should mention that following the incident we immediately communicated with the Pakistani government and strongly condemned this attack targeting Chinese. </seg>
<seg id="17"> We are now demanding that the Pakistani authorities make every effort to solve the case and severely...eh...severely punish the perpetrators. </seg>
<seg id="18"> We have asked the Pakistani authorities to take practical security measures to guarantee the physical and property security of our personnel and special project teams in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Following the incident, a local armed group called the Balochistan Liberation Army claimed responsibility for the attack, saying that the Chinese engineers had been killed because they were collaborating with the Pakistani government in stealing the mineral resources of the local tribal inhabitants. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Balochistan police described the incident as an open terrorist attack and said the armed militants has shot and killed innocent Chinese. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Pakistan's Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement promising to strengthen security safeguards for other Chinese engineering personnel and at the same time to intensify efforts to apprehend the killers who carried out the attack. </seg>
<seg id="22"> This is a news brief by Phoenix Satellite Television. </seg>
<seg id="23"> Elsewhere, the Pakistan Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement on the evening of the 15th strongly condemning the incident that afternoon in which three Chinese engineers were shot to death and called the incident an act of terrorism. </seg>
<seg id="24"> The statement said the government and people of Pakistan strongly condemn the shooting deaths of the Chinese engineers. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The government and people of Pakistan expressed their profound respect for the Chinese engineers who sacrificed their lives for the development of Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="26"> The Pakistan government and people expressed their deepest condolences to the families of the victims. </seg>
<seg id="27"> The statement also said the Pakistani government was determined to strengthen protection for Chinese citizens working in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="28"> The government would take every measure to prevent similar events from reoccurring in the future. </seg>
<seg id="29"> The statement also said that the shooting to death of the three Chinese engineers was a terrorist act committed in a vain attempt at creating a (()) in Sino-Pakistani relations. </seg>
<seg id="30"> The Pakistan government was determined not to allow such attempts to succeed. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Pakistan's law-enforcement authorities are taking steps to quickly apprehend the assailants and bring them to justice. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Moreover, Chinese President Hu Jintao  learned late on the night of the 15th that a gun attack on Chinese engineers and technicians in the Pakistani province of Balochistan had resulted in three deaths. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Eh...after learning the news, he expressed deep concern for the safety of Chinese technical personnel working in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Then, Hu Jintao, he immediately instructed the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and China's embassy and consulates in Pakistan to pressure the Pakistani authorities to apprehend the assailants, ensure the safety of Chinese personnel in Pakistan and, eh, appropriately handle arrangements related to those who were killed. </seg>
<seg id="35"> In addition, Hu Jintao also expressed profound sorrow for the tragic deaths of the Chinese personnel and expressed his sincere condolences to their families. </seg>
<seg id="36"> Okay, regarding this issue, we are now going to contact Chen Yiming, reporter for the People's Daily in Islamabad, in order to find out the newest developments. </seg>
<seg id="37"> Hello, Mr. Chen. </seg>
<seg id="38"> Can you give us the newest developments in the investigation into the shooting deaths of Chinese engineers? </seg>
<seg id="39"> Eh, yes, Anchorman. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Eh, from what I've been able to learn from the Chinese consulate-general in Karachi regarding the situation, the...eh...Chinese embassy and consulate have, uh, informed the unit to which the victim's belonged of the tragedy. </seg>
<seg id="41"> And, eh, according to standard procedure, then, uh, arrangements for the victim's remains should be carried out after consulting with their work unit and their, uh, families. </seg>
<seg id="42"> Furthermore, Pakistan's Ministry of Foreign Affairs also issued a statement yesterday. </seg>
<seg id="43"> Their, uh, statement said that, uh, the provocateurs in this incident were aiming to create tension in relations between China and Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="44"> Um, the statement says that a thorough investigation would be carried out into the incident and, eh, toward, uh, in Pakistan, eh, strengthen security and protection measure for all Chinese, eh, working in the country. It also says, um, the Pakistani authorities would do everything they could to prevent the reoccurrence of similar incidents. </seg>
<seg id="45"> Um, in addition, according to a report on the evening of the 15th by Pakistan's privately-owned television station GEO, the CEO of the Attock Cement Factory in Pakistan, Bashir, said that evening during, eh, in an interview with that station that in the aftermath of the attack Pakistan would organize as soon as possible the repatriation of the remaining eleven Chinese engineers and technicians working on the construction of the cement project. </seg>
<seg id="46"> And this Bashir also said during the interview that, in regard to questions by Pakistani media as to why, uh, at the time of the incident the Chinese engineers were not accompanied by security personnel, uh, he said, eh, that in actuality the cement plant where the engineers worked had its own security system but that because the location of the incident was still within the limits of the factory area there were no accompanying security personnel when the incident took place. </seg>
<seg id="47"> He expressed his extreme regret over the tragic incident. </seg>
<seg id="48"> Anchorman. </seg>
<seg id="49"> Um, okay. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Uh, in addition, this is actually not the first time that Chinese engineering personnel have been killed in attacks in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="51"> A similar incident occurred in October 2004. </seg>
<seg id="52"> Two Chinese engineers were kidnapped by an armed group in South Waziristan. </seg>
<seg id="53"> In the end, one of the individuals was tragically killed in the rescue operation. </seg>
<seg id="54"> Also, three engineers were killed in a bomb attack in Gwador in May of the same year. </seg>
<seg id="55"> Let's take a look back. </seg>
<seg id="56"> On May 3, 2004, in the port of Gwador in the south of the Pakistani province of Balochistan, a vehicle carrying twelve Chinese headed toward a worksite at the port was hit by a car bomb attack. </seg>
<seg id="57"> As a result, three Chinese engineers were killed and nine individuals were injured. </seg>
<seg id="58"> Local armed separatists and tribal militants are believed to have launched the attack. </seg>
<seg id="59"> On October 9 of the same year, two Chinese engineers were kidnapped by armed militants in the area of South Waziristan in the border region between Pakistan and Afghanistan. </seg>
<seg id="60"> A short while after, one engineer was fatally shot as Pakistani troops were rescuing the hostages. </seg>
<seg id="61"> However, it is believed that the hostage-taking was carried out by armed militants linked to Al Qaeda and not armed separatists. </seg>
<seg id="62"> Because China has close economic ties with Pakistan and participates in infrastructure projects in that country, several Chinese engineers work there. </seg>
<seg id="63"> On the other hand, there are also armed tribal groups in Pakistan that accuse the government of plundering their natural resources. </seg>
<seg id="64"> This has resulted in Chinese becoming the victims of attacks or kidnappings on several occasions. </seg>
<seg id="65"> This is a news brief by Phoenix Satellite Television. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PHOENIX_GOODMORNCN_CMN_20060215_185801_955_1163.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chh">
<seg id="1"> Let's take a look at some news items from  Japan. </seg>
<seg id="2"> Recently, Japan's political arena produced some rather sensational news. </seg>
<seg id="3"> That is, Tsuneo Watanabe, chairman of one of Japan's leading papers, the Yomiuri Shimbun, he ordered Yomiuri Shimbun to publish some articles ...eh ... that oppose Koizumi's visit to the Yasukuni Shrine, marking Yomiuri Shimbun's shift to a stand against Koizumi's visit to Yasukuni Shrine. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Eh ... so ... this Tsuneo Watanabe ..., in the speech he made a few days ago, he also lashed out at Koizumi ..., saying that he is ignorant and has no historical and cultural knowledge. </seg>
<seg id="5"> At the same time, he commented that visiting Yasukuni Shrine was just like paying tribute to Hitler and said that, in so doing, Koizumi ... eh ... had caused China and South Korea to ... eh ... regard Japan as a very dangerous country. This will bring endless troubles. </seg>
<seg id="6"> So why has Tsuneo Watanabe's attitude caused such a  repercussion? </seg>
<seg id="7"> In fact, he is very influential in political circles and has always been a major behind-the-scenes operator. </seg>
<seg id="8"> And he used to be a very rightist figure. </seg>
<seg id="9"> It should be said that he has always been a supporter of the hawks and strongly advocated revision of the constitution. </seg>
<seg id="10"> But, now, ... well ... this is really a major turn-around. </seg>
<seg id="11"> He turned his gun and ... eh ... opened fire  on Koizumi, adopting an attitude of opposition. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Actually, in 2004, when Koizumi was being criticized for visiting Yasukuni Shrine, this Tsuneo Watanabe ... he ... eh ... he said that he supported it and wanted Koizumi to withstand the pressure. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Recently, however, he made a speech, saying: "I am over 80 years old and don't have many days left." </seg>
<seg id="14"> So, he now stands up to make a high-profile speech with a very opposing attitude. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Such a turnaround of course produced a significant impact on the entire Japanese society. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Just as Tsuneo Watanabe himself put it, he said: "I am convinced that I have the strength to control and change the direction of the political winds." </seg>
<seg id="17"> And he also said that he would put up a desperate resistance if the government pressured Yomiuri Shimbun with respect to its freedom of speech or its ability to interview. </seg>
<seg id="18"> So, what has the situation come to now? </seg>
<seg id="19"> Well, Japan's largest newspaper, Yomiuri Shimbun, and the second largest newspaper, Asahi Shimbu...eh, these two leading newspapers have started to team up in opposition to Koizumi's visit to Yasukuni Shrine. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Originally, the two papers were opponents, but after the two chairmen met, they were able to reach agreement on this issue at least. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Therefore, they have now launched a campaign of considerable scale to criticize Koizumi. You can say that they have formed an ideal combination. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Actually, these two large newspapers have great sway over mainstream public opinion in Japan. </seg>
<seg id="23"> In a separate development, let's look at the meeting of the Japanese parliament. At a recent meeting, two candidates favored to succeed Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi made the same type of remarks. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Who were the two? </seg>
<seg id="25"> One was Chief Cabinet Secretary Shinzo Abe and the other was Minister for Foreign Affairs Taro Aso, who of late has frequently made astonishing remarks. </seg>
<seg id="26"> What did the two say? </seg>
<seg id="27"> They said that Japanese war criminals of the Second World War were not criminals. </seg>
<seg id="28"> What they mean is ... eh ... that, they claimed that these criminals ... it was the intention of the international court to convict them. </seg>
<seg id="29"> But, in Japan, according to international laws ... they were citing the domestic laws of Japan ... eh ... the war criminals ... did not break the domestic laws of Japan. </seg>
<seg id="30"> So, they think that, in Japan, World War II criminals should not be regarded as criminals. </seg>
<seg id="31"> This Shinzo Abe ... he also mentioned that Japan now ... eh ... should take the whole world into account, develop relations with the United States and develop commercial and trade relations with some East Asian countries, and, furthermore, it should also try to develop closer ties with India rather than always focus on China. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_LNTS_14974749cb4b6f49_CMN_20060216_084900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Chance at the Championship, But It's Not a Sure Thing </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Love life, love Lu Neng </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> The China Football Association Super League is set for some fierce battles. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Luneng Taishan is getting combat-ready for the new season with the championship in mind. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Hot competitions will be triggered between the Dalian, Shandong and Shanghai teams, the three strongest competitors for the championship. </seg>
<seg id="6"> In the end, who will win the championship? </seg>
<seg id="7"> Based on an analysis of their strengths, Taishan has a very good chance to become champion, but it is by no means a sure thing. </seg>
<seg id="8"> First of all, the new team members have not had long enough to get worked in. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Taishan lost at four major events last year. </seg>
<seg id="10"> This year, Taishan recruited two players from the national team--Li Leilei and Wang Liang. With the addition of two foreign players soon afterwards, it is safe to say that the team will be stronger. </seg>
<seg id="11"> But because the national football team is preparing for matches with Palestine and Iraq, there no way to say how well the two players from the national team will integrate. </seg>
<seg id="12"> By the time they return to the club, league matches will be set to begin. </seg>
<seg id="13"> That is why integration has become the most significant issue Taishan is facing. </seg>
<seg id="14"> In my view, the national-team players can be used as backups in the first few rounds of league matches. </seg>
<seg id="15"> First, team integration can be achieved using the in-game training. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Second, the national-team players who have just played group matches with the national team can use the lull to rest up. </seg>
<seg id="17"> After a few rounds, when the "knife is well sharpened', it will not be too late for them to play top spots. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, the defense has some weaknesses. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Last year, Taishan's fans had some unfavorable things to say about the team's defense. </seg>
<seg id="20"> This year, the defense will have improved with the recruitment of Li Leilei. But it's still not the time to sit back and relax. </seg>
<seg id="21"> There's still the problem of sluggish turnaround at the center back position, and the substitutes for this position are either too old or lacking in experience. </seg>
<seg id="22"> If performance at the center back position can be stabilized, Taishan will gain some momentum on the road to becoming champion. </seg>
<seg id="23"> In my opinion, they might as well use Ren Yongshun, who is strong physically. Although he lacks experience, he should be put to work this year so as to be ready in the future. </seg>
<seg id="24"> In addition, Gao Yao can play center back as well. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Taishan has quite a few players who can play defending midfield, such as Cui Peng and Hai Bing. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Gao Yao is physically very strong and a ferocious interceptor. He should be able to handle the center back position. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Another question is whether the foreign recruits can adjust. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Taishan has been plagued by problems with foreign recruits. </seg>
<seg id="29"> The performance of Daniel [Daniel Danciulescu] last year was far from stellar. </seg>
<seg id="30"> We know that this year's selection of foreign players has not yet been finalized. </seg>
<seg id="31"> I think that apart from bringing in an excellent striker, a true left-footed midfielder should also be recruited this year. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Except for Xing Rui, who played for the team a few years ago, Taishan has not had a true left-footed player with good skills. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Although players like Cui Peng and other can play the position, a truly competent left half back would be greatly preferred to fill-in. </seg>
<seg id="34"> If these three issues can be solved, Taishan's road to the championship should be somewhat smoother. </seg>
<seg id="35"> As a Shandong football fan, I'm really hoping Taishan can win the championship this year. </seg>
<seg id="36"> But to be frank, with things looking like they do in the championships this year, Taishan has a good chance, but it is far from a sure thing. </seg>
</DOC>
