<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_a6b18a4b27644df8_CMN_20060215_083500" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Envoys Hold Closed Door Talks with Chinese Officials </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Beili of the CGP </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dalai Lama's Envoys Hold Closed Door Talks with Chinese Officials. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Dalai Lama Stressed he Wants Autonomy, Not Independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Envoys of Tibet's exiled spiritual leader the Dalai Lama are in China for closed door talks with Chinese officials. Details have not yet been released. </seg>
<seg id="6"> This is the fifth official meeting since China and the Dalai Lama's exiled government resumed contacts in 2002. </seg>
<seg id="7"> But, as in the past, the two sides are meeting behind closed doors. No details have yet been disclosed. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Reporters say the two sides have held talks on several occasions, but so far there have been no tangible results. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Dalai Lama, who is in exile in Northern India, says he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet。 </seg>
<seg id="10"> China has refused to comment on the talks between the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="11"> But analysts say Beijing wants dialogue, partly because it fears the death of the 70-year-old spiritual leader in exile could lead to heightened sentiments among Tibetans unhappy with China rule. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Cultural Identity </seg>
<seg id="13"> The delegation from the Dalai Lama's exiled government is led by Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari. He was also the lead delegate in earlier talks. </seg>
<seg id="14"> A spokesman for the Tibetan government-in-exile said the round of talks that they had with Chinese officials in Switzerland in 2005 were very "intensive and frank" and this has given the Tibetan people hope. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The spokesman said their ultimate hope is to resolve the relevant issues on the basis of a negotiated settlement with the Chinese leadership so that the Tibetan people will have the freedom to preserve what is important to them, which is their cultural identity. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="16"> <POSTER>  CGP貝立 </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="17"> Dalai Lama's Envoy Reiterates Tibetan Independence is Not Being Sought </seg>
<seg id="18"> Dalai Lama to Visit Washington This Month </seg>
<seg id="19"> In the run-up to the Tibetan spiritual leader the Dalai Lama's trip to the US on November 8, his envoy has said that the Tibetan government-in-exile is not seeking Tibet's independence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said in Washington that he hopes that the Chinese government will truly protect Tibet's unique culture and traditions. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is expected that during his visit to the US next week the Dalai Lama will discuss the Tibet issue with President Bush in the hope that Bush will press the Chinese government to give Tibet genuine autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> In July of this year, envoys of the Dalai Lama's met with Beijing's officials in Berne for their first direct contact. </seg>
<seg id="23"> "Genuine Autonomy" </seg>
<seg id="24"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that in recent years talks between the Tibetan government-in-exile and the Chinese authorities has revealed some positive elements. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The envoys of the Dalai Lama found that the leaders in Beijing, particularly the delegates of the CCP's United Front Work Department, are more willing than in the past to listen to their opinions. </seg>
<seg id="26"> But Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said the Tibetan government-in-exile and the Chinese government still have several differences of opinion and are still far-apart in their standpoints. </seg>
<seg id="27"> He said that in the last five years the Tibetan government-in-exile has done its utmost to respond to China's demands in order to create a favorable negotiating environment. </seg>
<seg id="28"> In order to create a favorable negotiating environment on the Tibetan issue, China should refrain from blindly pressuring the Dalai Lama. </seg>
<seg id="29"> He said the Dalai Lama does not seek independence for Tibet and that Tibet is still a part of China, but that the Chinese government must protect Tibet's unique culture and "allow the Tibetan people genuine autonomy". </seg>
<seg id="30"> Furthermore, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that some Chinese people think that once the Dalai Lama has died the Tibet issue will disappear. </seg>
<seg id="31"> He said that this thinking is extremely dangerous because once the Dalai Lama is dead China will have lost a historic opportunity to solve the Tibet issue. </seg>
<seg id="32"> He said that the Chinese government only needs to respond to the Dalai Lama's demands and suggest a final means of resolution, then the Dalai Lama will no longer need to talk at the international level about the Tibet issue. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b07aeae684cbc1b7_CMN_20060209_051800" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> The Key Tools of Democracy: Negotiation and Compromise!(ZT) </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Hou Ze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I've just read a web friend's posting in "Awe-inspiring Righteousness--Mr. Li Guiren" </seg>
<seg id="4"> His (her) original words were "negotiation and compromise are key tools of democracy. Otherwise, divisions due to differences of opinion result in the failure of democracy!!! It is hoped that idealistic democracy advocates will pay close attention to this point!" </seg>
<seg id="5"> That this prosaic and colorless statement did not attract the interest of any web friends stired a succession of thoughts in my mind and filled me with regret. </seg>
<seg id="6"> I think about China's antiquity. I also think about the past in the west. </seg>
<seg id="7"> I, who have started very few threads, could not resist using a new thread to respond to the posting by the original net friend. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Let's first take a look at antiquity in China. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Everybody knows that in China, starting with the united centralized rule built by Qin Shi Huang, all subsequent dynasties operated according to this political framework. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Although the Han Dynasty temporarily implemented a "dual system"; that is, political system in which feudalism and centralism operated in parallel; it finally ended up employing centralism. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Under the historical conditions of that time, this kind of centralism had facets that were advanced or that promoted productivity and development. </seg>
<seg id="12"> But we should also observe that more than two thousand years of this kind of system resulted in localities that lacked the creativity, initiative and motivation that they should have. Furthermore, it was impossible to tailor-make systems and policies so that they suited local development. </seg>
<seg id="13"> A pyramid-shaped system of political rule also made it so that lower-level officials could only fix their gazes upward and in every regard take orders from their immediate superiors. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Because the local county officials were all appointed by the central government, there was no room for coordination or negotiation between them, let alone with the common people. </seg>
<seg id="15"> When the rights of peasants in ancient China were infringed upon, they could only grin and bear it. </seg>
<seg id="16"> It was only when their most basic rights were threatened, such as by large scale famine, or when their right to life was being deprived due to tyranny or natural calamity, that they would rise in rebellion. </seg>
<seg id="17"> In two thousand years, several turbulent peasant uprisings have swept across the entire country: from the unplanned Chen Sheng and Wu Guang Uprising to the preplanned Yellow Turban Rebellion, and then to the Huang Chao Rebellion in the Tang Dynasty and Li Zicheng, who was able to rule as emperor for a month as the result of an uprising. Besides Zhu Yuanzhang, none of the rebellions obtained a truly meaningful victory. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Even the Ming Dynasty that Zhu Yuanzhang initiated was nothing more than the reincarnation of previous dynasties, with no change in political institutions. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Zhu Yuanzhang, born a commoner and uncultured for the most part, manipulated China's ancient centralized system with a perverse relish, taking it to its extreme limits. The vigor of the Tang Dynasty, characterized by openness, freedom and tolerance, was lost and replaced by a deathly spiritlessness. </seg>
<seg id="20"> All at once, the atmosphere of free speech disappeared from China's vast area. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Human nature was suppressed to the highest degree. </seg>
<seg id="22"> People became timorous, extremely afraid, and unwilling to say too much. </seg>
<seg id="23"> This was the outcome of the only peasant uprising to succeed in two thousand years: in one go it turned the Chinese people into the living dead. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Now let's look at Western Europe's medieval period, which has been called the Dark Ages. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Middle Ages in Western Europe was a thousand year period that occurred after nomadic peoples destroyed Western Rome and that did not have the slightest connection to ancient Greece and ancient Rome. </seg>
<seg id="26"> This period was characterized by feudalism; that is, the granting of feudal land titles. </seg>
<seg id="27"> As titles were subdivided into increasingly lower strata, the lords at each lower stratum possessed an increased amount of autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Because they were capable of balancing, restricting and depending on each other both vertically and horizontally, even feudal lords with a few square kilometers of land as well as the dukes, marquises, earls, viscounts and barons that came to power possessed the conditions and clout to win from the king the rights that were rightfully theirs, thereby producing a situation where aristocrats and the king sat together to negotiate for their respective benefit, a situation that has never existed in China. </seg>
<seg id="29"> That is, mutual accommodation and concession, and not the use of violent methods to beat down and replace the other party. </seg>
<seg id="30"> In this way, with the drawing up various agreements, power steadily moved down into the hands of aristocrats and commoners. The power of the aristocrats and commoners gradually increased while the king's power progressively decreased. </seg>
<seg id="31"> By the time the Queen of England came along, she only occupied a passive position and did not have any real power. </seg>
<seg id="32"> This is how democracy was gradually achieved! </seg>
<seg id="33"> Let's take another look back in order to make a comparison. In ancient China, with all power concentrated in the hand of the emperor (with the exception of Li Shimin) and almost no aristocracy, it was almost impossible for peasants to sit with the emperor over a pot of tea or a glass of wine and light-heartedly make mutual compromises and concessions or formulate agreements that satisfied both sides. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Under such circumstances, when they were being deprived of their right to life, they had no choice but to adopt violent methods to overthrow the current dynasty in an attempt to supplant it. </seg>
<seg id="35"> This outcome repeated itself again and again, from the high point of the Tang Dynasty to the morbidity of the Ming Dynasty. </seg>
<seg id="36"> If we compare European and Chinese history, we discover that there is practically no western country with an ancient period where the contradictions between the rulers and the ruled were as sharp as in China. </seg>
<seg id="37"> There is no western country that experienced an endless succession of peasant uprisings like China did. </seg>
<seg id="38"> When contradictions arose between the royal house and the peasants in the ancient history of western countries, the first thing that aristocrats and commoners thought of when they were making an appeal for their own interests was to reach a solution through negotiation and make mutual concessions in order to gradually obtain greater benefits. Rarely did they employ violent methods. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Understanding this, as we enter the 21st century, we can still see on the Internet that there are some democracy militants who, having inherited the ultra-absolute totalitarian thinking of the Ming Dynasty, </seg>
<seg id="40"> and whose bodies have been invaded by the poison of the Cultural Revolution, are incapable as democratic warriors of talking about anything but "overthrow" and "toppling". </seg>
<seg id="41"> But this kind of thinking is the greatest barrier to democracy, because these people do not understand that negotiation and cooperation are the most important means and channel to realizing democracy. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b1314fab782e7592_CMN_20060209_044700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Cao Xiaoming--Rich Cultural Activities in the Countryside: Who Will "Pay the Bill"? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Hou Ze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> During this year's Spring Festival, I was fortunate enough to spend the New Year in the countryside visiting some family and friends. </seg>
<seg id="4"> While being caught up in the rich New Year's atmosphere in China's countryside, I also became worried about the lack of interesting cultural activities in rural areas. </seg>
<seg id="5"> I discovered in a friend's village that in past years the village would set out on its own each Spring Festival to organize the villagers in putting on a local play called "The Galloping Horse Lantern". </seg>
<seg id="6"> The play takes as its subject the characters from the Three Kingdoms. Adults and children can all enact a role in the play. The villagers never tire of watching. </seg>
<seg id="7"> In this way, there are several "Galloping Horse Lantern" performance troupes throughout the county. They perform not only in their own village, but also travel to other villages, with the exchange between villages becoming very lively. </seg>
<seg id="8"> But this year the village did not organize a troupe. </seg>
<seg id="9"> , It seems that it took a lot of money just to buy the costumes for "The Galloping Horse Lantern". In the past, the villagers would each contribute some cash, but now the costumes are tattered to the point that they can no longer be worn. </seg>
<seg id="10"> A house-to-house appeal was made to the villagers to again fork out money, but none was willing. A similar situation has arisen in other villages throughout the county. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Without the "Galloping Horse Lantern", the village has suddenly become cold and cheerless. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The adults have started playing mahjong. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The children have also started playing cards. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The villagers all say that this New Year's was dull. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Other than setting off firecrackers, everybody just played mahjong and that became the general backdrop of Chinese New Year in the countryside. </seg>
<seg id="16"> In addition, repeated bans have failed to halt a gambling craze that is showing a tendency to spread. Games involving upwards of ten thousand yuan have become a common occurrence, with the large number of returning migrant workers playing a particularly important role in many games. </seg>
<seg id="17"> In this way, money earned from a year of hard work is squandered. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Also, family squabbles stemming from gambling sometimes occur. Some even descend into tragedies where families are split or life is lost. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Some farmers say that they gamble not only during the Spring Festival, but also often during the slack season. </seg>
<seg id="20"> If they don't gamble, they don't have anywhere to go. </seg>
<seg id="21"> In the countryside, it is too difficult to organize cultural activities or find entertainment. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Not only is there a lack of facilities and funds, but also nobody volunteers to handle the organization. </seg>
<seg id="23"> In this respect, the method used in Jiangxi is doubtlessly welcome news for rural dwellers. </seg>
<seg id="24"> In order to enrich the cultural life of the rural population, the Jiangxi provincial government has not only implemented as of September last year a program of "government funding, market operation, town construction of stages and villagers watching plays", </seg>
<seg id="25"> but also organizes each year a special fund of at least Rmb60 million for rural cultural projects in order to provide the rural population high quality cultural products. </seg>
<seg id="26"> With the New Year, it added an additional Rmb40 million, making a rural cultural project fund totaling Rmb100 million. </seg>
<seg id="27"> For the rural population, the fruits of this special fund are also very substantial: </seg>
<seg id="28"> They invite various types of professional performance troupes to come to the villages to perform. Each village cannot have less than four performances each year. </seg>
<seg id="29"> They invite screening teams from different levels of movie companies and organizations to come to the villages to show movies. Each administrative village cannot have less than six screenings of entertainment and educational films each year. </seg>
<seg id="30"> They organize and hold popular cultural events that have local character. Each village cannot have less than two or three each year. </seg>
<seg id="31"> From this "purchase list", we can easily see that the government has not thrown money at the problem, but rather has expended a lot of energy to use limited funds in an incisive way in order to deliver a cultural feast with good value to the vast rural population. They have performed an important task. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Now, not an individual among the vast rural population is not ecstatic about the waiver of the grain tax. </seg>
<seg id="33"> If governments could do like Jiangxi and make greater "purchases" to enrich the cultural life of the rural population, it would be another gift from heaven for those living in the countryside, </seg>
<seg id="34"> and this "gift" would not only free the farmers from the mahjong table, the movement in cultural activities would also add another brick in socialist construction of a new countryside. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_d6c87f9f9950da31_CMN_20060214_106700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="chh">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Kidnap Warning for Wang Peirong's Child Was a False Alarm </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  peirongwangsohu@gmail.com </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Kidnap Warning for Wang Peirong's Child Was a False Alarm </seg>
<seg id="4"> After nine o'clock on the evening of January 24, 2006, the child of Wang Peirong finished relating the following: </seg>
<seg id="5"> While making up classes in physics at Xuzhou's No. 3 Middle School on the morning of January 24, 2006, Wang Peirong's child was called out by the entrance guard. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The entrance guard informed Wang Peirong's child that three unidentified men had said the following to the entrance guards of No. 3 Middle School:  Wang Peirong's child, Wang Tianjiao, has not returned home for three days because the father and mother of Wang Peirong's child are not getting along. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Now her mother is missing. We are leaders from her mother's work unit and want to enter No. 3 Middle School to get Wang Peirong's child. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Wang Peirong's child told the entrance guards that what the three men had said was completely untrue and she refused to go with the three men. </seg>
<seg id="9"> With the help of the entrance guards of No. 3 Middle School, Wang Peirong's child was not taken away. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Wang Peirong's child phoned her mother's leader at noon to find out what was going on. The leader denied sending anybody to Xuzhou's No. 3 middle school. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Wang Peirong's child asked her for the phone number of her father's leader. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Wang Peirong's child called her father's leader. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Wang Peirong's child said: Three people came to No. 3 Middle School to take me away. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The leader asked: Why didn't you go with them? </seg>
<seg id="15"> Wang Peirong's child answered: If I had gone with them I would be dead for sure. </seg>
<seg id="16"> When she had finished speaking, Wang Peirong's child hung up the phone. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Hearing a description of the events from his child, Wang Peirong felt that the situation was serious and reported it to the police. </seg>
<seg id="18"> On January 25, the local police station received feedback that the story told by Wang Peirong's child was essentially true. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The police station asked the Kuangda Security Department if they had sent people to the No. 3 Middle School to get Wang Peirong's child. They responded that they hadn't. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The police station again asked the Kuangda Security Department if any of its branch units had sent people to No. 3 Middle School to get Wang Peirong's child. They again answered that they hadn't. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Through them, the relevant departments warned Wang Peirong and his family to pay attention to their safety. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Following the event, the leaders of the relevant departments of Xuzhou municipality paid close attention. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The criminal investigation department of the Xuzhou Public Security Bureau excluded the possibility of a kidnap attempt against the child. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Wang Peirong thanked the relevant department heads of the Xuzhou municipality and the criminal investigation department of Xuzhou Public Security Department. </seg>
<seg id="25"> It was a false alarm. The main cause of the false alarm was possibly the entrance guards of No. 3 Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="26"> The criminal investigation department of the Xuzhou Public Security Bureau has learned: On January 24, the leader of the College of Science, which is Wang Peirong's work unit, and three other individuals urgently needed to find Wang Peirong (Wang Peirong still does not know why they were looking for him) and could not find him  by telephone. They thought of going to No. 3 Middle School to find the teacher of Wang Peirong's child in order to ask if Wang Peirong's child was still in Xuzhou. </seg>
<seg id="27"> A weighty topic: Why is the risk involved in corruption relatively low while the cost of fighting corruption is high? </seg>
<seg id="28"> http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&typeid=39 </seg>
<seg id="29"> Under the present cadre system and anti-corruption system, what corrupt officials need to be worry about is a few relevant officials overseeing them, not the broad masses of people. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Therefore, once they feel that they have successfully hoodwinked or contented those few officials that can determine their fate, they can they feel reassured and unafraid as they carry out their great project of corruptly and illegally collecting wealth while disregarding the feelings of the nearby masses of people. </seg>
<seg id="31"> On the contrary, if the common people who don't hold any power come across an injustice and stand up against corruption, they will possibly provoke an extremely brutal reprisal, </seg>
<seg id="32"> or be branded by the government and end up at any time being crushed in defeat before obtaining any victory. </seg>
<seg id="33"> A comparison of the two: engaging in corruption is relatively risk free, while the cost of resisting corruption on the other hand is high. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Entire article is found on the following webpage: http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&typeid=39 </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060207_145800_396_582.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chi">
<seg id="1"> Now let's take a look at the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The International Atomic Energy Agency verified on the 6th that the Iranian government had sent a letter to the International Atomic Energy Agency demanding that it dismantle and remove all equipment monitoring Iran's nuclear facilities by the middle of this month. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Because the International Atomic Energy Agency decided to report the Iran nuclear issue to the United Nations Security Council, Iran has announced the termination of all support and cooperation measures it had adopted with respect to the nuclear issue, and it will not longer permit the International Atomic Energy Agency to perform surprise inspections of its nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Targeting the current tense situation with respect to the Iranian nuclear issue, Russian foreign minister Lavrov said on the 6th in Athens that the cooperation between Russia and Iran still exists. </seg>
<seg id="5"> This will become the driving force in the resolution of the Iran nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="6"> On the same day, a spokesperson for the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs said that Russia's proposal to Iran to establish a joint uranium enrichment enterprise within Russia's borders was still effective. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The two parties could engage in negotiations concerning this issue next week. </seg>
<seg id="8"> On the same day, at United Nations headquarters in New York, Senator Lugar, chairman of the United States Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said that the United States does not approve of Israeli attacks of Iran's nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="9"> According to recent reports, Israeli defense experts have said that, if necessary, Israel could severely damage Iran's nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Xinhua News Agency reports that on the 7th, Russian deputy foreign minister Kislyak said Russia is willing to cooperate with Iran regarding the nuclear issue and help Iran obtain the legal authority to peacefully develop nuclear energy. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Kislyak said that Russia's proposal to Iran to establish a joint uranium enrichment enterprise with Iran remains valid. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Russia hopes to hold negotiations with Iran concerning this issue in the near future. </seg>
<seg id="13"> At the end of December last year, Russia submitted a proposal to Iran that the two countries establish a joint uranium enrichment enterprise within Russia's borders. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The European Union and the United States both said that they could accept this compromise proposal. </seg>
<seg id="15"> But Iran hopes Russia will continue to revise the original plan. </seg>
<seg id="16"> On the 7th, Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs spokesperson Kong Quan said that although the International Atomic Energy Agency had reported the Iran atomic energy problem to the United Nations Security Council, it had not transferred the agency's responsibility to handle the Iranian nuclear issue to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Therefore, the various parties must still break the deadlock over the Iran nuclear issue within the framework of the International Atomic Energy Agency. </seg>
<seg id="18"> According to a resolution of the International Atomic Energy Agency, International Atomic Energy Agency General Director Baradei will deliver a report concerning the Iran nuclear issue to the Security Council in March. </seg>
<seg id="19"> After evaluating this report, the Security Council will make a final decision. </seg>
<seg id="20"> We feel that this resolution mentions requiring Iran to, uh, fulfill the relevant Security Council resolutions and the promises it has made, and has not submitted or transferred this problem to the Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="21"> For some time recently, China has sought a peaceful resolution to the Iran nuclear issue through diplomatic means. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Kong Quan said that on February 1, Zhang Yan, Director-General of the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs Department of Arms Control and Disarmament, held talks in Tehran concerning the Iran nuclear issue with Lalijiani, negotiating representative of the Secretariat of the Supreme Security Council of Iran. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The Chinese hope Iran will attach importance to the international community as the key to creating conditions for a peaceful resolution of the Iranian nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Resolution of the Iranian nuclear issue within the IAEA framework is not only in China's interests; moreover, we firmly believe that it is in the interests of all parties. </seg>
<seg id="25"> To this end, we once again call on the concerned parties in the international community to not abandon the diplomatic efforts made regarding this issue. </seg>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060208_145800_256_429.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="chi">
<seg id="1"> Hamas, which is currently in the process of forming the new Palestinian self-rule government, has announced that, with the exception of the prime minister, the nominees for the new government's cabinet are essentially in place. </seg>
<seg id="2"> This has triggered all manner of speculation among outsiders concerning the selection of the prime minister. </seg>
<seg id="3"> On the 8th, a senior Hamas official disclosed to the Associated Press that Hamas was prepared to nominate ((businessman)) Khudari, chairman of the board of trustees of Islamic University in Gaza, but this nomination has yet to be formally submitted to Abbas. </seg>
<seg id="4"> With the support of Hamas, Khudari, who is now 51, participated in Palestine's parliamentary election last month as an independent candidate. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Khudari has never mentioned violence or opposition to Israel in his public speeches. </seg>
<seg id="6"> But he has said that Palestine must engage in internal reform. </seg>
<seg id="7"> A high-level Hamas delegation is currently visiting Cairo to discuss the issue of Hamas' formation of the new Palestinian Authority government. </seg>
<seg id="8"> On the 8th, Khaled Masha'al, a member of the delegation, told the press that despite the constant pressure from the international community and certain Arab countries, the Palestinian government formed by Hamas leaders would not recognize Israel. </seg>
<seg id="9"> At the same time, Masha'al warned Abbas in his statement: do not arbitrarily change the structure of Palestinian leadership without consulting Hamas in advance. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Analysts believe that this was in response to Abbas' plan to appoint interior minister Yousef as deputy commander of security forces. </seg>
